const QUESTIONS = [
  // ── HISTORY (15 questions) ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
  {"id":1,"topic":"History","topicIcon":"📜","q":"Which philosophical position holds that knowledge comes primarily from heredity and innate biological factors?","opts":["Empiricism","Nativism","Functionalism","Behaviorism"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Nativism (associated with Plato, Descartes) argues knowledge is inbuilt through heredity, contrasting with empiricism's view that knowledge comes from experience."},
  {"id":2,"topic":"History","topicIcon":"📜","q":"John Locke's concept of the mind at birth is best described as:","opts":["A wax tablet full of innate ideas","A blank slate (tabula rasa)","A hierarchical network","A parallel processor"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Locke argued that the mind at birth is a blank slate (tabula rasa) and that all knowledge comes from experience."},
  {"id":3,"topic":"History","topicIcon":"📜","q":"William Wundt established the first scientific psychology laboratory in which year and city?","opts":["1859, London","1879, Leipzig","1900, Vienna","1913, New York"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Wundt founded the first experimental psychology laboratory in Leipzig, Germany in 1879, marking the birth of scientific psychology."},
  {"id":4,"topic":"History","topicIcon":"📜","q":"Wundt's structuralism attempted to study consciousness by:","opts":["Observing only external behaviour","Breaking mental processes into basic sensations and feelings","Studying evolutionary adaptations","Mapping neural networks"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Structuralism broke consciousness into its component sensations and feelings, analogous to how chemistry breaks compounds into elements."},
  {"id":5,"topic":"History","topicIcon":"📜","q":"Which school of psychology argued that the function of mental processes—not their structure—is what matters?","opts":["Structuralism","Gestalt","Functionalism","Connectionism"],"ans":2,"diff":"easy","expl":"Functionalism, associated with William James and influenced by Darwin, focused on how mental processes function and adapt rather than their component parts."},
  {"id":6,"topic":"History","topicIcon":"📜","q":"The Gestalt principle that 'the whole is always more than the sum of its parts' directly opposes which school?","opts":["Functionalism","Behaviorism","Structuralism","Connectionism"],"ans":2,"diff":"medium","expl":"Gestalt psychology opposed structuralism's reductionist approach, arguing that breaking mental experience into parts destroys the meaning of the whole."},
  {"id":7,"topic":"History","topicIcon":"📜","q":"Behaviorism, as championed by Skinner, insisted that psychology should study only:","opts":["Mental images and consciousness","Stimulus, response, and consequences","Neural firing patterns","Evolutionary adaptations"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Behaviorism rejected unobservable mental states and focused exclusively on observable stimulus-response relationships and their consequences."},
  {"id":8,"topic":"History","topicIcon":"📜","q":"The cognitive revolution was largely triggered by the development of:","opts":["The printing press","Computers and information processing models","Brain imaging technology","Evolutionary biology"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"The development of computers gave cognitive psychologists a model for understanding mental processes as information processing, sparking the cognitive revolution."},
  {"id":9,"topic":"History","topicIcon":"📜","q":"Which paradigm views cognition as information passing through a series of processing systems?","opts":["Connectionism","Evolutionary approach","Information processing approach","Ecological approach"],"ans":2,"diff":"easy","expl":"The information processing approach models cognition as information flowing through systems (sensory memory → STM → LTM), each performing specific operations."},
  {"id":10,"topic":"History","topicIcon":"📜","q":"Connectionism (parallel distributed processing) proposes that mental experience arises from:","opts":["A single central processor","Many small interconnected units with weighted connections","A hierarchy of schemas","Evolutionary modules"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Connectionism holds that cognition emerges from networks of many small units connected with varying weights, not from a single large symbolic processor."},
  {"id":11,"topic":"History","topicIcon":"📜","q":"The evolutionary approach to cognitive psychology emphasises that some cognitive abilities, such as language and depth perception, are:","opts":["Learned entirely through experience","Inbuilt through natural selection","Products of cultural context","Dependent on working memory capacity"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"The evolutionary approach argues that certain cognitive competencies are biologically prepared through natural selection, not purely learned."},
  {"id":12,"topic":"History","topicIcon":"📜","q":"The ecological approach to cognition stresses that cognitive activities:","opts":["Occur in isolation from culture","Are shaped by the culture and context in which they occur","Are best studied in laboratory settings only","Depend solely on neural architecture"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"The ecological approach holds that cognition is always embedded in cultural and environmental context, which shapes how information is processed."},
  {"id":13,"topic":"History","topicIcon":"📜","q":"In Sternberg's memory search experiment, as the length of the memorised list increased, verification time:","opts":["Decreased","Stayed the same","Increased linearly","Increased exponentially"],"ans":2,"diff":"medium","expl":"Sternberg found that verification time increased linearly with list length, supporting a serial exhaustive search model of memory access."},
  {"id":14,"topic":"History","topicIcon":"📜","q":"The Atkinson-Shiffrin modal model of memory includes which three stores?","opts":["Iconic, echoic, haptic","Sensory register, short-term memory, long-term memory","Phonological loop, visuospatial sketchpad, central executive","Episodic, semantic, procedural"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"The Atkinson-Shiffrin (1968) modal model proposes three sequential stores: sensory register, short-term memory, and long-term memory."},
  {"id":15,"topic":"History","topicIcon":"📜","q":"Plato's metaphor for memory compared it to:","opts":["A computer hard drive","Writings on a wax tablet","A filing cabinet","A neural network"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Plato described memory as writings on a wax tablet; the strength and clarity of the impressions determined the strength of memories."},

  // ── METHODS (15 questions) ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
  {"id":16,"topic":"Methods","topicIcon":"🔬","q":"Which behavioural method measures the percentage of correct responses to assess processing effectiveness?","opts":["Reaction time","Accuracy","Protocol analysis","Judgment scale"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"The accuracy method records the percentage of correct responses, providing an objective measure of how effectively a mental process is working."},
  {"id":17,"topic":"Methods","topicIcon":"🔬","q":"The 'ceiling effect' in accuracy measurement occurs when:","opts":["A task is too difficult and no one succeeds","A task is too easy and everyone scores at maximum","Reaction times are too fast to measure","Participants refuse to respond"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"A ceiling effect occurs when a task is so easy that all participants score at the maximum, making it impossible to detect differences in processing."},
  {"id":18,"topic":"Methods","topicIcon":"🔬","q":"The speed-accuracy trade-off means that as accuracy requirements increase:","opts":["Speed also increases","Speed decreases (more time is needed)","Both speed and accuracy improve","Neither changes"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"There is an inverse relationship: demanding higher accuracy forces slower, more careful processing, reducing speed."},
  {"id":19,"topic":"Methods","topicIcon":"🔬","q":"In the protocol analysis method, participants are asked to:","opts":["Rate their experience on a scale","Verbally announce what they are doing mentally","Press a button as fast as possible","Draw what they perceive"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Protocol analysis (think-aloud) requires participants to verbalise their ongoing mental steps, revealing the sequence of cognitive processes."},
  {"id":20,"topic":"Methods","topicIcon":"🔬","q":"EEG (electroencephalography) is characterised by excellent temporal resolution but poor:","opts":["Cost efficiency","Temporal resolution","Spatial resolution","Non-invasiveness"],"ans":2,"diff":"medium","expl":"EEG records electrical potentials from the scalp with millisecond precision (excellent temporal resolution) but cannot pinpoint the exact brain region (poor spatial resolution)."},
  {"id":21,"topic":"Methods","topicIcon":"🔬","q":"MEG (magnetoencephalography) records which type of brain signal?","opts":["Electrical potentials from the scalp","Magnetic fields generated by neuronal activity","Blood oxygen levels","Radioactive isotope accumulation"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"MEG captures the tiny magnetic fields produced by neuronal electrical activity, offering both good spatial and temporal resolution."},
  {"id":22,"topic":"Methods","topicIcon":"🔬","q":"PET scanning using the O-15 isotope works by detecting:","opts":["Magnetic alignment of atoms","Accumulation of radioactive oxygen in active brain regions","Electrical potentials on the scalp","Laser light reflected from brain tissue"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"PET with O-15 water detects increased blood flow (and thus radioactive oxygen accumulation) in brain regions active during a cognitive task."},
  {"id":23,"topic":"Methods","topicIcon":"🔬","q":"fMRI measures brain activity by detecting:","opts":["Electrical potentials","Magnetic fields from neurons","Blood oxygen level-dependent (BOLD) signal","Radioactive decay"],"ans":2,"diff":"easy","expl":"fMRI uses the BOLD signal—the ratio of oxygenated to deoxygenated blood—to infer which brain regions are active during a task."},
  {"id":24,"topic":"Methods","topicIcon":"🔬","q":"Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (TMS) is classified as a causal method because it:","opts":["Correlates brain activity with behaviour","Temporarily disrupts activity in a specific brain region","Measures electrical potentials","Records blood flow changes"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"TMS uses magnetic pulses to temporarily disrupt neural activity in a targeted region, allowing researchers to establish causal links between that region and behaviour."},
  {"id":25,"topic":"Methods","topicIcon":"🔬","q":"A dissociation in cognitive neuroscience occurs when:","opts":["Two tasks activate the same brain region","A variable affects performance on one task but not another","Two methods give identical results","Participants perform equally on all tasks"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Dissociation is demonstrated when a manipulation (e.g., brain lesion or task load) impairs one cognitive process but leaves another intact, suggesting they rely on different mechanisms."},
  {"id":26,"topic":"Methods","topicIcon":"🔬","q":"An association in cognitive neuroscience is found when:","opts":["Two different processes activate the same brain region","One process is impaired while another is spared","Reaction times are identical across conditions","Accuracy reaches ceiling"],"ans":0,"diff":"medium","expl":"An association occurs when two different cognitive processes converge on the same brain area, suggesting shared neural mechanisms."},
  {"id":27,"topic":"Methods","topicIcon":"🔬","q":"The 'experimental expectancy effect' is a limitation of which behavioural method?","opts":["Accuracy","Reaction time","Protocol analysis","Judgment"],"ans":1,"diff":"hard","expl":"In reaction time studies, participants may detect the experimenter's expectations and adjust their response speed accordingly, confounding results."},
  {"id":28,"topic":"Methods","topicIcon":"🔬","q":"Optical imaging of the brain works on the principle that:","opts":["The brain emits radio waves","The brain is transparent to certain light wavelengths","Neurons generate magnetic fields","Blood is radioactive"],"ans":1,"diff":"hard","expl":"Optical imaging uses near-infrared light, which passes through brain tissue; the speed of reflection varies with blood flow, indicating neural activity."},
  {"id":29,"topic":"Methods","topicIcon":"🔬","q":"Box models in cognitive psychology represent:","opts":["Neural network weights","Discrete processing stages connected by arrows","Brain anatomy","Evolutionary modules"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Box models (e.g., Atkinson-Shiffrin) depict cognition as a series of discrete processing boxes (stages) connected by arrows showing information flow."},
  {"id":30,"topic":"Methods","topicIcon":"🔬","q":"Which method has the highest invasiveness among the neural correlational methods?","opts":["EEG","MEG","PET","fMRI"],"ans":2,"diff":"medium","expl":"PET requires injection of a radioactive isotope into the bloodstream, making it the most invasive of the common neuroimaging correlational methods."},

  // ── PERCEPTION (15 questions) ───────────────────────────────────────────────
  {"id":31,"topic":"Perception","topicIcon":"👁️","q":"The object as it physically exists in the environment is called the:","opts":["Proximal stimulus","Percept","Distal stimulus","Retinal image"],"ans":2,"diff":"easy","expl":"The distal stimulus is the actual object in the environment. The proximal stimulus is the image it casts on the retina, and the percept is the brain's interpretation."},
  {"id":32,"topic":"Perception","topicIcon":"👁️","q":"The inverted image formed on the retina is called the:","opts":["Distal stimulus","Proximal stimulus","Percept","Pattern"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"The proximal stimulus is the retinal image—the physical representation of the distal stimulus on the sensory surface."},
  {"id":33,"topic":"Perception","topicIcon":"👁️","q":"Pattern recognition is best defined as:","opts":["Detecting edges in a visual scene","Recognising an object as belonging to a particular class","Measuring the intensity of light","Separating figure from ground"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Pattern recognition is the process of comparing incoming sensory information with stored representations to classify an object or event."},
  {"id":34,"topic":"Perception","topicIcon":"👁️","q":"The Gestalt principle of proximity states that objects that are close together are:","opts":["Perceived as moving together","Perceived as belonging together","Perceived as similar in colour","Perceived as figure rather than ground"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Proximity: nearby elements are grouped perceptually, even if they differ in other properties."},
  {"id":35,"topic":"Perception","topicIcon":"👁️","q":"Which Gestalt principle explains why we see alternating rows of red and white dots as two separate rows?","opts":["Proximity","Similarity","Good continuation","Closure"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Similarity: elements that share visual features (colour, shape) are grouped together, so red dots cluster with red and white with white."},
  {"id":36,"topic":"Perception","topicIcon":"👁️","q":"The Gestalt principle of good continuation suggests that we group elements whose contours form:","opts":["Closed shapes","Straight or smoothly curved lines","Similar colours","Common motion"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Good continuation: elements that form a smooth, continuous line or curve are grouped together, even if they could be parsed differently."},
  {"id":37,"topic":"Perception","topicIcon":"👁️","q":"When the brain 'fills in' a gap to perceive an incomplete circle as a whole circle, this illustrates:","opts":["Proximity","Similarity","Closure","Common fate"],"ans":2,"diff":"easy","expl":"Closure: the perceptual system completes incomplete figures, filling gaps to create the simplest, most complete interpretation."},
  {"id":38,"topic":"Perception","topicIcon":"👁️","q":"The Gestalt principle of common fate groups objects that:","opts":["Are close together","Look similar","Move in the same direction","Form a closed shape"],"ans":2,"diff":"easy","expl":"Common fate: elements moving in the same direction at the same speed are perceived as belonging to the same group."},
  {"id":39,"topic":"Perception","topicIcon":"👁️","q":"The Law of Pragnanz (Prägnanz) states that perception tends toward:","opts":["The most complex interpretation","The simplest and most stable interpretation","The most colourful interpretation","The largest figure"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Pragnanz (good form): the perceptual system always seeks the simplest, most regular, and most stable interpretation of a stimulus."},
  {"id":40,"topic":"Perception","topicIcon":"👁️","q":"Size constancy refers to the perceptual tendency to:","opts":["See objects as larger when they are closer","Perceive an object's size as stable despite changes in retinal image size","Group similar objects together","Perceive depth from monocular cues"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Size constancy: we perceive objects as the same size regardless of distance, even though the retinal image shrinks as objects move away."},
  {"id":41,"topic":"Perception","topicIcon":"👁️","q":"Reversible figures (e.g., the old/young woman illusion) demonstrate that:","opts":["Perception is purely bottom-up","The same proximal stimulus can yield different percepts depending on figure-ground assignment","Gestalt principles always produce unique percepts","Colour is the primary cue for object recognition"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Reversible figures show that perception is not determined solely by the stimulus; top-down factors like attention and expectation influence which interpretation dominates."},
  {"id":42,"topic":"Perception","topicIcon":"👁️","q":"Gibson's concept of 'affordances' refers to:","opts":["The physical properties of light waves","The action possibilities an object offers to an observer","The number of features in a visual scene","The depth cues available in an image"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Gibson argued that when we perceive an object we also directly perceive its affordances—the actions it invites (e.g., a chair affords sitting)."},
  {"id":43,"topic":"Perception","topicIcon":"👁️","q":"In figure-ground perception, which statement is true?","opts":["The background is remembered better than the figure","The figure tends to have better-defined shape and is remembered better","Both figure and ground are equally salient","Ground always appears in front of the figure"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Figures have clearer contours and are remembered better; backgrounds are less defined and serve as context for the figure."},
  {"id":44,"topic":"Perception","topicIcon":"👁️","q":"Sensation differs from perception in that sensation:","opts":["Involves interpretation of stimuli","Is the raw input detected by sensory organs before interpretation","Requires prior knowledge","Depends on top-down processing"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Sensation is the detection of physical energy by sensory receptors; perception is the subsequent interpretation and meaning-making process."},
  {"id":45,"topic":"Perception","topicIcon":"👁️","q":"Which Gestalt principle is considered the overarching law that encompasses all other principles?","opts":["Proximity","Similarity","Law of Pragnanz","Common fate"],"ans":2,"diff":"medium","expl":"The Law of Pragnanz is the master principle: the perceptual system always seeks the simplest, most stable organisation, which underlies all other Gestalt principles."},

  // ── ATTENTION – BASIC (15 questions) ────────────────────────────────────────
  {"id":46,"topic":"Attention","topicIcon":"🎯","q":"Selective attention is best described as:","opts":["Processing all incoming stimuli equally","Focusing cognitive resources on one stimulus while filtering others","Dividing attention equally among tasks","Automatically processing stimuli without awareness"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Selective attention is the ability to focus on one stimulus or task while ignoring competing stimuli, acting like a filter on incoming information."},
  {"id":47,"topic":"Attention","topicIcon":"🎯","q":"The dichotic listening task, designed by Cherry in 1953, involves:","opts":["Participants watching two videos simultaneously","Participants receiving different messages in each ear and shadowing one","Participants counting tones while reading","Participants detecting targets in a visual display"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"In Cherry's dichotic listening task, different messages are presented to each ear via headphones, and participants shadow (repeat aloud) one ear's message."},
  {"id":48,"topic":"Attention","topicIcon":"🎯","q":"'Shadowing' in the dichotic listening paradigm means:","opts":["Ignoring the attended message","Repeating aloud whatever is heard in the designated ear","Writing down what is heard","Pressing a button when a target word is heard"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Shadowing requires participants to immediately repeat aloud the message from the attended ear, ensuring active attention to that channel."},
  {"id":49,"topic":"Attention","topicIcon":"🎯","q":"From Cherry's (1953) experiment, participants could report which of the following from the unattended ear?","opts":["The exact words spoken","The language of the message","The gender of the speaker","The meaning of the message"],"ans":2,"diff":"medium","expl":"Cherry found that from the unattended ear, participants could detect physical properties like the speaker's gender, whether it was speech or noise, and speech direction—but not the content or language."},
  {"id":50,"topic":"Attention","topicIcon":"🎯","q":"Broadbent's filter theory (1958) proposes that the attentional filter operates based on:","opts":["Semantic meaning of messages","Physical properties of stimuli (e.g., pitch, location)","Emotional significance","Prior knowledge"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Broadbent's early-selection filter theory holds that the filter selects messages based on physical characteristics (location, pitch, loudness) before semantic analysis."},
  {"id":51,"topic":"Attention","topicIcon":"🎯","q":"The cocktail party phenomenon, described by Moray (1959), demonstrates that:","opts":["People cannot hear anything from the unattended channel","One's own name can penetrate the attentional filter from the unattended channel","Attention is always fully allocated to one channel","Physical properties alone determine what is attended"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Moray showed that personally significant stimuli (like one's own name) can break through the attentional filter from the unattended channel, challenging Broadbent's strict filter theory."},
  {"id":52,"topic":"Attention","topicIcon":"🎯","q":"Broadbent's filter theory is classified as an 'early selection' model because:","opts":["Selection occurs after full semantic analysis","Selection occurs based on physical features before semantic processing","It was proposed early in the history of psychology","It applies only to early childhood"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Early selection models (like Broadbent's) propose that the filter acts on physical features before the message is analysed for meaning, blocking unattended messages early."},
  {"id":53,"topic":"Attention","topicIcon":"🎯","q":"In Broadbent's filter theory, what happens to unattended messages?","opts":["They are fully processed for meaning","They are held briefly in a sensory buffer and then blocked","They are stored in long-term memory","They are processed in parallel with attended messages"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Broadbent proposed that unattended messages are held briefly in a pre-attentive sensory buffer but are blocked by the filter before semantic processing."},
  {"id":54,"topic":"Attention","topicIcon":"🎯","q":"Attention span refers to:","opts":["The total amount of information one can process","The duration for which attention can be maintained on a single stimulus","The number of tasks one can perform simultaneously","The speed of attentional switching"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Attention span is the length of time a person can concentrate on a particular stimulus or task before attention shifts elsewhere."},
  {"id":55,"topic":"Attention","topicIcon":"🎯","q":"According to Broadbent, two messages can both be processed when:","opts":["Both messages are semantically rich","The messages contain minimal information or are presented very slowly","The listener is highly motivated","The messages are in different languages"],"ans":1,"diff":"hard","expl":"Broadbent allowed that two channels could be processed simultaneously only if each contained very little information or was presented at a slow rate, not exceeding cognitive capacity."},
  {"id":56,"topic":"Attention","topicIcon":"🎯","q":"Treisman's experiment where the attended message switched ears showed that participants:","opts":["Immediately followed the switch to the new ear","Continued shadowing the original message for a few words after the switch","Stopped shadowing entirely","Reported the content of both ears equally"],"ans":1,"diff":"hard","expl":"Treisman found that participants continued to shadow the original message for a few words even after it switched ears, demonstrating that 100% attention was devoted to the content, not the physical channel."},
  {"id":57,"topic":"Attention","topicIcon":"🎯","q":"William James' early view on attention was that it:","opts":["Can be focused on multiple stimuli simultaneously","Can only be focused on one stimulus at a time","Is entirely automatic","Improves indefinitely with practice"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"James argued that attention can only be truly focused on one thing at a time; apparent multi-tasking reflects rapid switching rather than true simultaneous attention."},
  {"id":58,"topic":"Attention","topicIcon":"🎯","q":"The dichotic listening task is useful for studying attention because:","opts":["It eliminates all sensory input","It creates a controlled situation where one channel is attended and one is not","It measures reaction time precisely","It requires no instructions to participants"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"By having participants shadow one ear, the dichotic task creates a clear attended vs. unattended channel, allowing researchers to study what information passes the attentional filter."},
  {"id":59,"topic":"Attention","topicIcon":"🎯","q":"Moray (1959) found that approximately what percentage of participants heard their own name from the unattended ear?","opts":["100%","75%","30%","5%"],"ans":2,"diff":"hard","expl":"Moray reported that about 30% of participants detected their own name in the unattended channel, showing that personally significant stimuli can penetrate the filter."},
  {"id":60,"topic":"Attention","topicIcon":"🎯","q":"The primary reason studying attention is methodologically challenging is that:","opts":["Attention cannot be measured","Instructing participants not to attend to something causes them to attend to it","Attention has no neural correlates","Attention is identical across all individuals"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"The paradox of attention research is that telling someone not to pay attention to something immediately draws their attention to it, making experimental control difficult."},

  // ── ATTENTION – MODELS & AUTOMATIZATION (15 questions) ──────────────────────
  {"id":61,"topic":"Attention","topicIcon":"🎯","q":"Treisman's attenuation theory differs from Broadbent's filter theory in that unattended messages are:","opts":["Completely blocked","Attenuated (reduced in strength) rather than fully blocked","Processed for full meaning","Stored in long-term memory"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Treisman proposed that the filter attenuates (turns down the volume of) unattended messages rather than blocking them entirely, allowing important stimuli to still reach awareness."},
  {"id":62,"topic":"Attention","topicIcon":"🎯","q":"Late selection theory proposes that the attentional bottleneck occurs:","opts":["Before any semantic analysis","After messages have been analysed for meaning","At the level of physical features","During motor response selection"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Late selection models argue that all incoming messages are processed for meaning, and selection occurs later—at the stage of response or conscious awareness."},
  {"id":63,"topic":"Attention","topicIcon":"🎯","q":"Johnston and Heinz's (1978) multimodal theory states that attentional selection can occur at:","opts":["Only one fixed stage","Three flexible stages depending on task demands","Only the semantic level","Only the physical feature level"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"The multimodal theory proposes three stages of selection (sensory, semantic, combined), with the stage used depending on how similar the competing messages are."},
  {"id":64,"topic":"Attention","topicIcon":"🎯","q":"In Kahneman's capacity model, 'enduring dispositions' refer to:","opts":["Momentary environmental demands","Long-term interests and habits that guide attention allocation","The total amount of available cognitive capacity","Arousal level"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Enduring dispositions are stable personal interests and habits (e.g., a musician attending to music) that influence how attentional resources are allocated."},
  {"id":65,"topic":"Attention","topicIcon":"🎯","q":"In Kahneman's capacity model, 'momentary intentions' are:","opts":["Stable personality traits","Immediate, context-driven goals that redirect attention","The baseline arousal level","Automatic processing routines"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Momentary intentions are transient, goal-directed states (e.g., deciding to listen for a specific word) that temporarily redirect attentional allocation."},
  {"id":66,"topic":"Attention","topicIcon":"🎯","q":"Kahneman's capacity model proposes that the total available attentional capacity is influenced by:","opts":["Only task difficulty","Arousal level","Only the number of tasks","Only prior knowledge"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Kahneman argued that arousal level modulates the total pool of available cognitive capacity—higher arousal generally increases available capacity up to an optimal point."},
  {"id":67,"topic":"Attention","topicIcon":"🎯","q":"Neisser's schema theory of attention proposes that unattended stimuli are:","opts":["Attenuated but still processed","Not perceived at all—attention works as an all-or-none system","Stored in sensory memory","Processed for physical features only"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Neisser's schema theory treats attention as all-or-none: what you don't attend to is simply not perceived, like unpicked fruit remaining on a tree."},
  {"id":68,"topic":"Attention","topicIcon":"🎯","q":"Inattentional blindness refers to the failure to notice:","opts":["Objects that are too small to see","Unexpected objects or events that appear in plain sight when attention is focused elsewhere","Changes in colour of attended objects","Objects presented to the unattended ear"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Inattentional blindness occurs when attention is fully engaged on a task, causing people to miss unexpected but clearly visible stimuli (e.g., the gorilla in the ball-passing experiment)."},
  {"id":69,"topic":"Attention","topicIcon":"🎯","q":"Schneider and Shiffrin (1977) distinguished between consistent mapping and varied mapping. In consistent mapping:","opts":["Target and distractor sets overlap and change each trial","Target items are always targets and distractors are always distractors, enabling automaticity","Participants must search exhaustively every trial","Reaction time increases with set size"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Consistent mapping (same items always targets) leads to automatic detection after practice; varied mapping (targets and distractors swap) requires controlled search throughout."},
  {"id":70,"topic":"Attention","topicIcon":"🎯","q":"According to Snyder and Posner (1975), automatic processes are characterised by which three criteria?","opts":["Speed, accuracy, and flexibility","No intention, no conscious awareness, and no interference with other tasks","High effort, serial processing, and conscious control","Slow onset, high accuracy, and parallel processing"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Automatic processes (Snyder & Posner) require no intention to initiate, occur without conscious awareness, and do not interfere with concurrent tasks."},
  {"id":71,"topic":"Attention","topicIcon":"🎯","q":"Treisman's feature integration theory proposes that in the pre-attentive stage:","opts":["Features are bound together into objects","Individual features are registered in parallel without attention","Objects are identified by name","Attention is required for every feature"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"In the pre-attentive stage, basic features (colour, orientation, size) are registered automatically and in parallel across the visual field without focused attention."},
  {"id":72,"topic":"Attention","topicIcon":"🎯","q":"Illusory conjunctions in feature integration theory occur when:","opts":["Attention is fully focused on a target","Features from different objects are incorrectly combined due to insufficient attention","Objects are presented for too long","The visual field contains only one object"],"ans":1,"diff":"hard","expl":"Illusory conjunctions happen when attention is overloaded or absent; features from nearby objects are incorrectly bound together (e.g., seeing a red X when there is a red O and a blue X)."},
  {"id":73,"topic":"Attention","topicIcon":"🎯","q":"The 'pop-out' phenomenon in visual search occurs when:","opts":["A target shares features with all distractors","A target has a unique feature that makes it immediately salient regardless of display size","Search time increases linearly with set size","Attention is required to find the target"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Pop-out occurs when a target differs from distractors on a single basic feature (e.g., a red item among green items); it is detected pre-attentively and search time does not increase with set size."},
  {"id":74,"topic":"Attention","topicIcon":"🎯","q":"The psychological refractory period (PRP) refers to:","opts":["The time needed to recover from sleep deprivation","The delay in responding to a second stimulus when it closely follows a first","The time for automatic processes to develop","The duration of the attentional blink"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"The PRP is the slowing of response to a second stimulus (S2) when it is presented shortly after a first stimulus (S1), because the cognitive system is still processing S1."},
  {"id":75,"topic":"Attention","topicIcon":"🎯","q":"Attentional capture refers to:","opts":["The voluntary direction of attention to a chosen target","The involuntary drawing of attention by a salient or unexpected stimulus","The gradual improvement of attention with practice","The failure to detect an expected stimulus"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Attentional capture is the automatic, involuntary shift of attention toward a stimulus that is physically salient (e.g., sudden onset, high contrast) or personally significant."},

  // ── MEMORY – INTRODUCTION & STM (15 questions) ──────────────────────────────
  {"id":76,"topic":"Memory","topicIcon":"🧠","q":"In the Atkinson-Shiffrin modal model, which store holds information for the briefest duration?","opts":["Short-term memory","Long-term memory","Sensory register","Episodic buffer"],"ans":2,"diff":"easy","expl":"The sensory register (sensory memory) holds information for a fraction of a second to a few seconds before it decays or is transferred to STM."},
  {"id":77,"topic":"Memory","topicIcon":"🧠","q":"The primacy effect in the serial position curve is attributed to:","opts":["Items at the end of a list being in STM","Items at the beginning of a list having been rehearsed into LTM","Items in the middle being most distinctive","Recency of presentation"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Early list items benefit from more rehearsal opportunities, allowing them to be transferred to LTM, producing better recall—the primacy effect."},
  {"id":78,"topic":"Memory","topicIcon":"🧠","q":"The recency effect in the serial position curve is attributed to:","opts":["Items at the beginning being in LTM","Items at the end still being in STM at the time of recall","Items in the middle being rehearsed most","Semantic similarity of end items"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"The most recently presented items are still in STM at the time of recall, producing the recency effect—better recall for the last few items."},
  {"id":79,"topic":"Memory","topicIcon":"🧠","q":"Iconic memory is the sensory store for which modality?","opts":["Auditory","Haptic","Visual","Olfactory"],"ans":2,"diff":"easy","expl":"Iconic memory is the brief visual sensory store; echoic memory is auditory, and haptic memory is for touch."},
  {"id":80,"topic":"Memory","topicIcon":"🧠","q":"Sperling's (1960) partial-report experiments demonstrated that iconic memory:","opts":["Holds only 4 items","Holds a large amount of visual information but it decays very rapidly","Is unlimited in capacity and duration","Is the same as short-term memory"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Sperling showed that the iconic store holds nearly all items from a briefly presented array, but the information decays within about 250–500 ms, so only a partial report is possible."},
  {"id":81,"topic":"Memory","topicIcon":"🧠","q":"Miller's (1956) 'magical number' for STM capacity is:","opts":["3 ± 1 chunks","5 ± 1 chunks","7 ± 2 chunks","9 ± 2 chunks"],"ans":2,"diff":"easy","expl":"Miller proposed that STM can hold approximately 7 ± 2 chunks of information, regardless of the complexity of each chunk."},
  {"id":82,"topic":"Memory","topicIcon":"🧠","q":"Chunking in STM refers to:","opts":["Forgetting information in blocks","Grouping individual items into larger meaningful units to increase effective capacity","Rehearsing items one at a time","Transferring items to LTM"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Chunking reorganises individual items into larger meaningful units (e.g., remembering 'FBI' as one chunk rather than three letters), effectively expanding STM capacity."},
  {"id":83,"topic":"Memory","topicIcon":"🧠","q":"Conrad's (1964) experiment showed that errors in STM recall tend to be:","opts":["Semantically similar to the target","Acoustically similar to the target","Visually similar to the target","Random"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Conrad found that STM errors involved acoustically similar letters (e.g., B confused with P, V), suggesting STM uses primarily acoustic/phonological coding."},
  {"id":84,"topic":"Memory","topicIcon":"🧠","q":"The Brown-Peterson task is used to study:","opts":["LTM encoding","Decay of information from STM when rehearsal is prevented","Chunking capacity","Semantic coding in LTM"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"In the Brown-Peterson task, participants recall a trigram after a filled delay (counting backwards) that prevents rehearsal, demonstrating rapid decay from STM."},
  {"id":85,"topic":"Memory","topicIcon":"🧠","q":"Proactive interference in STM occurs when:","opts":["New information interferes with recall of old information","Old information interferes with recall of new information","Decay removes information over time","Rehearsal strengthens a memory trace"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Proactive interference: previously learned material interferes with the learning and recall of new material (old interferes forward with new)."},
  {"id":86,"topic":"Memory","topicIcon":"🧠","q":"Wickens and Born's (1963) 'release from proactive interference' demonstrated that:","opts":["Proactive interference is permanent","Switching to a new category of items reduces proactive interference","Rehearsal eliminates proactive interference","Proactive interference only affects LTM"],"ans":1,"diff":"hard","expl":"When the category of items changed (e.g., from numbers to letters), recall improved dramatically—'release from PI'—showing that PI is category-specific."},
  {"id":87,"topic":"Memory","topicIcon":"🧠","q":"The Waugh-Norman probe digit task was designed to test which theory of STM forgetting?","opts":["Decay theory","Interference theory","Encoding failure","Retrieval failure"],"ans":1,"diff":"hard","expl":"Waugh and Norman used the probe digit task to pit decay against interference; they found that interference (number of intervening items) was the primary cause of STM forgetting."},
  {"id":88,"topic":"Memory","topicIcon":"🧠","q":"Sternberg's serial search model of STM proposes that memory search is:","opts":["Parallel and self-terminating","Serial and exhaustive","Random and probabilistic","Parallel and exhaustive"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Sternberg proposed that STM search is serial (one item at a time) and exhaustive (the entire list is scanned before a response is made), supported by the linear increase in RT with list length."},
  {"id":89,"topic":"Memory","topicIcon":"🧠","q":"Echoic memory is the sensory store for which modality?","opts":["Visual","Auditory","Haptic","Olfactory"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Echoic memory is the auditory sensory store, holding sounds for approximately 3–4 seconds—longer than iconic memory's ~250 ms."},
  {"id":90,"topic":"Memory","topicIcon":"🧠","q":"Which of the following best describes the capacity of long-term memory?","opts":["7 ± 2 chunks","Limited to about 1000 items","Effectively unlimited","Exactly 100 items"],"ans":2,"diff":"easy","expl":"Unlike STM, LTM is considered to have effectively unlimited capacity; there is no known upper bound on how much information can be stored in LTM."},

  // ── WORKING MEMORY (15 questions) ───────────────────────────────────────────
  {"id":91,"topic":"Working Memory","topicIcon":"💭","q":"The working memory model was proposed by:","opts":["Atkinson and Shiffrin","Baddeley and Hitch","Miller and Chomsky","Craik and Lockhart"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Baddeley and Hitch (1974) proposed the working memory model as a replacement for the unitary STM concept, comprising multiple specialised components."},
  {"id":92,"topic":"Working Memory","topicIcon":"💭","q":"The central executive in Baddeley's working memory model is responsible for:","opts":["Storing phonological information","Maintaining visual-spatial information","Coordinating the slave systems and allocating attentional resources","Providing a link to long-term memory"],"ans":2,"diff":"easy","expl":"The central executive is the supervisory component that controls and coordinates the phonological loop and visuospatial sketchpad, and allocates attentional resources."},
  {"id":93,"topic":"Working Memory","topicIcon":"💭","q":"The phonological loop consists of which two sub-components?","opts":["Central executive and episodic buffer","Phonological buffer and articulatory rehearsal process","Visuospatial sketchpad and inner scribe","Semantic store and phonological store"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"The phonological loop has a phonological store (holds sound-based information for ~2 seconds) and an articulatory rehearsal process (the 'inner voice' that refreshes the store)."},
  {"id":94,"topic":"Working Memory","topicIcon":"💭","q":"The visuospatial sketchpad in working memory is responsible for:","opts":["Rehearsing verbal information","Maintaining and manipulating visual and spatial information","Linking working memory to LTM","Coordinating dual tasks"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"The visuospatial sketchpad (the 'inner eye') holds and manipulates visual images and spatial information, such as mental maps or object shapes."},
  {"id":95,"topic":"Working Memory","topicIcon":"💭","q":"The episodic buffer, added by Baddeley in 2000, serves to:","opts":["Replace the central executive","Provide a temporary multi-modal store that links working memory components with LTM","Store only visual information","Rehearse phonological information"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"The episodic buffer is a limited-capacity store that integrates information from the phonological loop, visuospatial sketchpad, and LTM into coherent episodes."},
  {"id":96,"topic":"Working Memory","topicIcon":"💭","q":"The dual-task paradigm is used to study working memory by:","opts":["Presenting two lists of words sequentially","Having participants perform two tasks simultaneously to identify shared resources","Measuring reaction time to single stimuli","Comparing recall of words and pictures"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"The dual-task paradigm requires participants to perform two tasks at once; if performance on one task suffers when the other is added, they share a common working memory resource."},
  {"id":97,"topic":"Working Memory","topicIcon":"💭","q":"In Baddeley and Hitch's (1974) reasoning task with digit load, adding a digit span task:","opts":["Completely eliminated reasoning ability","Slowed reasoning slightly but did not eliminate it","Had no effect on reasoning","Improved reasoning performance"],"ans":1,"diff":"hard","expl":"Baddeley and Hitch found that a concurrent digit span task slowed reasoning but did not prevent it, suggesting that reasoning and verbal rehearsal share some but not all working memory resources."},
  {"id":98,"topic":"Working Memory","topicIcon":"💭","q":"Which component of working memory would be most disrupted by a concurrent spatial tapping task?","opts":["Phonological loop","Central executive","Visuospatial sketchpad","Episodic buffer"],"ans":2,"diff":"medium","expl":"A spatial tapping task occupies the visuospatial sketchpad, disrupting tasks that require spatial processing (e.g., mental rotation, navigation)."},
  {"id":99,"topic":"Working Memory","topicIcon":"💭","q":"Articulatory suppression (repeating 'the, the, the') disrupts which working memory component?","opts":["Visuospatial sketchpad","Central executive","Episodic buffer","Phonological loop"],"ans":3,"diff":"medium","expl":"Articulatory suppression occupies the articulatory rehearsal process of the phonological loop, preventing verbal rehearsal and disrupting phonological storage."},
  {"id":100,"topic":"Working Memory","topicIcon":"💭","q":"The word-length effect in working memory refers to the finding that:","opts":["Longer words are remembered better","Fewer long words than short words can be held in the phonological loop","Words with more syllables are recalled faster","Word length has no effect on STM"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"The word-length effect: people can recall more short words than long words from a list, because the articulatory loop can hold about 2 seconds of speech, fitting more short words."},
  {"id":101,"topic":"Working Memory","topicIcon":"💭","q":"The phonological similarity effect shows that STM recall is worse for:","opts":["Words that are semantically similar","Words that sound similar to each other","Words that are visually similar","Long words compared to short words"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Phonologically similar words (e.g., cat, bat, hat) are harder to recall from STM because they create confusion in the phonological store."},
  {"id":102,"topic":"Working Memory","topicIcon":"💭","q":"Working memory is considered more useful than the simple STM concept because it:","opts":["Has greater capacity","Explains how memory is used during active cognitive tasks like reasoning and comprehension","Is easier to measure","Has no capacity limits"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Working memory captures the active, dynamic nature of short-term storage—it explains how we hold and manipulate information while performing complex cognitive tasks."},
  {"id":103,"topic":"Working Memory","topicIcon":"💭","q":"Which component of working memory is most closely associated with language comprehension?","opts":["Visuospatial sketchpad","Episodic buffer","Phonological loop","Central executive"],"ans":2,"diff":"medium","expl":"The phonological loop supports language comprehension by maintaining the sound of words and sentences while they are being processed."},
  {"id":104,"topic":"Working Memory","topicIcon":"💭","q":"The central executive is analogous to which concept in attention research?","opts":["Sensory register","Supervisory attentional system (SAS)","Phonological buffer","Episodic LTM"],"ans":1,"diff":"hard","expl":"The central executive functions like Norman and Shallice's Supervisory Attentional System—it monitors, controls, and coordinates cognitive processes, especially in novel or difficult situations."},
  {"id":105,"topic":"Working Memory","topicIcon":"💭","q":"Evidence that the phonological loop and visuospatial sketchpad are separate systems comes from:","opts":["The word-length effect alone","Double dissociation: tasks that disrupt one component do not disrupt the other","The primacy effect","Miller's 7±2 finding"],"ans":1,"diff":"hard","expl":"Double dissociation evidence (e.g., articulatory suppression disrupts verbal but not spatial tasks; spatial tapping disrupts spatial but not verbal tasks) confirms the two systems are independent."},

  // ── LONG-TERM MEMORY (15 questions) ─────────────────────────────────────────
  {"id":106,"topic":"Long-Term Memory","topicIcon":"📚","q":"Baddeley's experiment on LTM coding showed that LTM primarily uses:","opts":["Acoustic coding","Visual coding","Semantic coding","Haptic coding"],"ans":2,"diff":"medium","expl":"Baddeley demonstrated that LTM errors are semantically similar (not acoustically similar), showing that LTM relies primarily on meaning-based (semantic) encoding."},
  {"id":107,"topic":"Long-Term Memory","topicIcon":"📚","q":"Ebbinghaus's forgetting curve shows that forgetting is:","opts":["Linear over time","Rapid at first and then levels off","Slow at first and then accelerates","Constant across all time intervals"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Ebbinghaus found that most forgetting occurs rapidly soon after learning, with the rate of forgetting slowing down over time—a negatively accelerating curve."},
  {"id":108,"topic":"Long-Term Memory","topicIcon":"📚","q":"Craik and Lockhart's levels of processing framework proposes that:","opts":["Rehearsal time determines memory strength","Deeper, more meaningful processing leads to stronger, more durable memories","The number of repetitions is the only factor in LTM encoding","Acoustic processing produces the best memories"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Levels of processing: shallow processing (e.g., physical features) produces weak memories; deep, semantic processing (e.g., meaning) produces stronger, more durable memories."},
  {"id":109,"topic":"Long-Term Memory","topicIcon":"📚","q":"Elaborative rehearsal differs from maintenance rehearsal in that it:","opts":["Simply repeats information without adding meaning","Connects new information to existing knowledge, producing deeper encoding","Is faster but less effective","Only works for procedural memories"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Elaborative rehearsal involves thinking about the meaning of information and connecting it to existing knowledge, producing deeper processing and better LTM encoding than simple repetition."},
  {"id":110,"topic":"Long-Term Memory","topicIcon":"📚","q":"Declarative memory includes which two subtypes?","opts":["Procedural and semantic","Episodic and semantic","Iconic and echoic","Explicit and implicit"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Declarative (explicit) memory is divided into episodic memory (personal events) and semantic memory (general world knowledge)."},
  {"id":111,"topic":"Long-Term Memory","topicIcon":"📚","q":"Procedural memory stores:","opts":["Personal autobiographical events","General factual knowledge","Skills and how-to knowledge","Emotional associations"],"ans":2,"diff":"easy","expl":"Procedural memory is implicit memory for skills and procedures (e.g., riding a bike, typing), which are performed without conscious recollection."},
  {"id":112,"topic":"Long-Term Memory","topicIcon":"📚","q":"Priming in LTM refers to:","opts":["Deliberately rehearsing information","Improved processing of a stimulus due to prior exposure to a related stimulus","Forgetting due to interference","Encoding failure"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Priming is an implicit memory effect where prior exposure to a stimulus facilitates faster or more accurate processing of a related stimulus later."},
  {"id":113,"topic":"Long-Term Memory","topicIcon":"📚","q":"Encoding failure theory of forgetting proposes that:","opts":["Information was encoded but cannot be retrieved","Information was never properly encoded into LTM in the first place","Memories decay over time","New memories interfere with old ones"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Encoding failure: forgetting occurs because the information was never adequately encoded into LTM, so there is nothing to retrieve."},
  {"id":114,"topic":"Long-Term Memory","topicIcon":"📚","q":"The encoding specificity principle (Tulving) states that:","opts":["Deeper encoding always leads to better recall","Memory is best when retrieval conditions match encoding conditions","Spaced practice always outperforms massed practice","Semantic coding is always superior"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Encoding specificity: the cues present at encoding, when reinstated at retrieval, maximise recall—context and state at encoding should match retrieval conditions."},
  {"id":115,"topic":"Long-Term Memory","topicIcon":"📚","q":"The context-dependent memory effect (Godden & Baddeley's divers experiment) showed that:","opts":["Underwater learning is always superior","Recall is best when the environment at retrieval matches the environment at encoding","Emotional state has no effect on memory","Semantic coding overrides context effects"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Divers who learned material underwater recalled it better underwater; those who learned on land recalled better on land—demonstrating context-dependent memory."},
  {"id":116,"topic":"Long-Term Memory","topicIcon":"📚","q":"State-dependent memory refers to better recall when:","opts":["The physical environment matches encoding","The internal physiological/emotional state at retrieval matches the state at encoding","Semantic processing was used","Spaced practice was used"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"State-dependent memory: recall is better when the internal state (e.g., mood, drug state) at retrieval matches the state at encoding."},
  {"id":117,"topic":"Long-Term Memory","topicIcon":"📚","q":"The spacing effect (distributed practice) shows that:","opts":["Massed practice (cramming) leads to better long-term retention","Spaced practice leads to better long-term retention than massed practice","The two methods produce identical results","Spacing only helps for procedural memory"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"The spacing effect: distributing practice over time (spaced practice) produces better long-term retention than the same amount of practice concentrated in one session (massed practice)."},
  {"id":118,"topic":"Long-Term Memory","topicIcon":"📚","q":"Bartlett's 'War of the Ghosts' study demonstrated that LTM recall is:","opts":["A perfect reproduction of the original","Reconstructive, influenced by schemas and prior knowledge","Purely acoustic in nature","Unaffected by cultural background"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Bartlett showed that participants' recall of an unfamiliar Native American story was systematically distorted to fit their own cultural schemas, demonstrating reconstructive memory."},
  {"id":119,"topic":"Long-Term Memory","topicIcon":"📚","q":"Loftus's eyewitness testimony research showed that:","opts":["Eyewitness memory is highly accurate","Leading questions can alter the content of eyewitness memories","Emotional arousal always improves eyewitness accuracy","Eyewitnesses never confabulate"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Loftus demonstrated that post-event information (e.g., leading questions) can be incorporated into memory, altering what witnesses report—showing the malleability of LTM."},
  {"id":120,"topic":"Long-Term Memory","topicIcon":"📚","q":"The tip-of-the-tongue (TOT) phenomenon is best explained by:","opts":["Encoding failure","Decay of the memory trace","Partial retrieval—the memory exists but cannot be fully accessed","Proactive interference"],"ans":2,"diff":"medium","expl":"TOT states occur when a memory is partially accessible (e.g., knowing the first letter or number of syllables) but cannot be fully retrieved, suggesting retrieval failure rather than encoding failure."},

  // ── SEMANTIC MEMORY (15 questions) ──────────────────────────────────────────
  {"id":121,"topic":"Semantic Memory","topicIcon":"🕸️","q":"Tulving (1972) distinguished episodic memory from semantic memory. Semantic memory stores:","opts":["Personal autobiographical events with time and place","General world knowledge and facts independent of personal experience","Procedural skills","Sensory impressions"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Semantic memory contains general factual knowledge (e.g., 'Paris is the capital of France') that is not tied to a specific personal experience or time."},
  {"id":122,"topic":"Semantic Memory","topicIcon":"🕸️","q":"Episodic memory stores:","opts":["General facts about the world","Personal events tied to a specific time and place","Motor skills","Semantic networks"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Episodic memory is autobiographical memory for personally experienced events, including contextual details of when and where they occurred."},
  {"id":123,"topic":"Semantic Memory","topicIcon":"🕸️","q":"Collins and Quillian's (1969) hierarchical network model proposes that concepts are stored as:","opts":["Separate, unconnected nodes","Nodes in a hierarchy with properties stored at the highest applicable level (cognitive economy)","Prototypes with graded membership","Exemplars from personal experience"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Collins and Quillian's model stores concepts in a hierarchy (e.g., animal → bird → canary) with properties stored at the highest level where they apply, saving storage space (cognitive economy)."},
  {"id":124,"topic":"Semantic Memory","topicIcon":"🕸️","q":"'Cognitive economy' in Collins and Quillian's model means:","opts":["Concepts are retrieved as quickly as possible","Properties are stored at the highest applicable node rather than repeated at every lower node","Memory capacity is unlimited","Retrieval requires no effort"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Cognitive economy: to avoid redundancy, properties shared by all members of a category (e.g., 'has skin' for all animals) are stored once at the superordinate level, not repeated for each subordinate."},
  {"id":125,"topic":"Semantic Memory","topicIcon":"🕸️","q":"A key prediction of Collins and Quillian's model is that verifying 'A canary is an animal' should take longer than 'A canary is a bird' because:","opts":["'Animal' is a less familiar word","More hierarchical levels must be traversed to reach 'animal'","'Bird' has more features than 'animal'","Canaries are more typical birds than animals"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"The model predicts that verification time increases with the number of hierarchical links between the concept and the property node; 'animal' is two levels above 'canary', 'bird' is only one."},
  {"id":126,"topic":"Semantic Memory","topicIcon":"🕸️","q":"The feature comparison model of semantic memory distinguishes between:","opts":["Episodic and semantic features","Defining features (necessary) and characteristic features (typical but not necessary)","Superordinate and subordinate features","Visual and verbal features"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"The feature comparison model (Smith et al.) separates defining features (necessary for category membership, e.g., 'has wings' for bird) from characteristic features (typical but not required, e.g., 'can fly')."},
  {"id":127,"topic":"Semantic Memory","topicIcon":"🕸️","q":"Collins and Loftus's (1975) spreading activation model proposes that:","opts":["Concepts are stored in a strict hierarchy","Activation spreads from a concept to related concepts along associative links, with strength decreasing with distance","All concepts are equally accessible","Retrieval is always serial and exhaustive"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Spreading activation: activating one concept (e.g., 'fire') spreads activation to related concepts (e.g., 'red', 'hot', 'truck') along weighted links, facilitating their retrieval."},
  {"id":128,"topic":"Semantic Memory","topicIcon":"🕸️","q":"The typicality effect in semantic memory refers to the finding that:","opts":["All members of a category are verified equally quickly","Typical members (e.g., robin as a bird) are verified faster than atypical members (e.g., penguin as a bird)","Atypical members are always rejected","Category size determines verification time"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Typicality effect: typical category members (those sharing more features with the prototype) are verified faster and more accurately than atypical members."},
  {"id":129,"topic":"Semantic Memory","topicIcon":"🕸️","q":"Anderson's ACT-R model includes which three memory components?","opts":["Sensory, short-term, long-term","Declarative memory, working memory, and procedural memory (production rules)","Phonological loop, visuospatial sketchpad, central executive","Episodic, semantic, procedural"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"ACT-R (Anderson, 1976) comprises declarative memory (facts), working memory (active information), and procedural memory (production rules: if-then condition-action pairs)."},
  {"id":130,"topic":"Semantic Memory","topicIcon":"🕸️","q":"Scripts in semantic memory are:","opts":["Visual images of scenes","Schematic knowledge structures representing the typical sequence of events in familiar situations","Lists of defining features","Hierarchical taxonomies"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Scripts (Schank & Abelson) are knowledge structures that represent the typical sequence of events in routine situations (e.g., going to a restaurant), guiding comprehension and behaviour."},
  {"id":131,"topic":"Semantic Memory","topicIcon":"🕸️","q":"Tulving's 'bookshelf metaphor' for semantic memory suggests that:","opts":["Semantic memory is organised alphabetically","Semantic memory is organised by category, like books on a shelf by topic","Semantic memory is unorganised","Semantic memory is stored in a single location"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Tulving used the bookshelf metaphor to illustrate that semantic memory is organised by category/topic, allowing efficient retrieval of related information."},
  {"id":132,"topic":"Semantic Memory","topicIcon":"🕸️","q":"A limitation of Collins and Quillian's hierarchical network model is that it cannot explain:","opts":["Why verification takes longer for distant nodes","Typicality effects (e.g., why 'robin is a bird' is verified faster than 'penguin is a bird')","Why cognitive economy is useful","Why concepts are stored in nodes"],"ans":1,"diff":"hard","expl":"The strict hierarchy predicts equal verification time for all members at the same level, but typicality effects show that typical members are verified faster—a finding the model cannot account for."},
  {"id":133,"topic":"Semantic Memory","topicIcon":"🕸️","q":"In spreading activation models, the strength of activation between two concepts depends on:","opts":["Alphabetical proximity","The strength of the associative link between them","The number of syllables in each word","Their position in the hierarchy"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"In spreading activation models, activation spreads more strongly along well-established, frequently used associative links and weakens with distance and weaker links."},
  {"id":134,"topic":"Semantic Memory","topicIcon":"🕸️","q":"The false memory effect in semantic memory (e.g., DRM paradigm) occurs because:","opts":["People have poor attention","Spreading activation causes related but unstudied words to be falsely recognised","Semantic memory has no organisation","Episodic memory interferes with semantic memory"],"ans":1,"diff":"hard","expl":"In the DRM paradigm, studying semantically related words (e.g., bed, rest, tired) activates the non-presented associate (sleep), which is then falsely recognised—a consequence of spreading activation."},
  {"id":135,"topic":"Semantic Memory","topicIcon":"🕸️","q":"Production rules in ACT-R are best described as:","opts":["Declarative facts stored in LTM","If-then condition-action pairs that specify how to respond when certain conditions are met","Visual images of procedures","Episodic memories of past actions"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Production rules in ACT-R are procedural knowledge in the form 'IF [condition] THEN [action]', specifying how to act when particular conditions are present in working memory."},

  // ── CONCEPTS & CATEGORIES (15 questions) ────────────────────────────────────
  {"id":136,"topic":"Concepts","topicIcon":"🗂️","q":"The classical view of concepts holds that category membership is determined by:","opts":["Similarity to a prototype","Necessary and sufficient defining features","Exemplars stored in memory","Explanatory theories"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"The classical view: a concept is defined by a set of necessary and sufficient features; an item is a category member if and only if it has all the defining features."},
  {"id":137,"topic":"Concepts","topicIcon":"🗂️","q":"A major problem with the classical view of concepts is that:","opts":["It predicts typicality effects","Many natural categories lack clear necessary and sufficient features (e.g., 'game')","It cannot explain basic-level categories","It requires too much memory"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Wittgenstein's 'family resemblance' argument showed that many everyday concepts (e.g., game) have no single set of necessary and sufficient features, undermining the classical view."},
  {"id":138,"topic":"Concepts","topicIcon":"🗂️","q":"The prototype view of concepts proposes that category membership is determined by:","opts":["Necessary and sufficient features","Similarity to the most typical or average member (prototype)","Matching to stored exemplars","Causal-explanatory theories"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Prototype theory: categories are represented by an abstract prototype (the most typical member), and new items are classified by their similarity to this prototype."},
  {"id":139,"topic":"Concepts","topicIcon":"🗂️","q":"The exemplar view of concepts proposes that categories are represented by:","opts":["An abstract prototype","A set of defining features","Specific remembered instances (exemplars)","Causal theories"],"ans":2,"diff":"easy","expl":"Exemplar theory: categories are represented by stored memories of specific instances; new items are classified by their similarity to these stored exemplars."},
  {"id":140,"topic":"Concepts","topicIcon":"🗂️","q":"Rosch's basic level of categorisation (e.g., 'dog') is preferred over superordinate ('animal') and subordinate ('poodle') levels because:","opts":["It has the most features","It provides the best balance of informativeness and cognitive efficiency","It is always the shortest word","It is learned first in all cultures"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Basic-level categories (e.g., dog, chair) are cognitively privileged: they are the most informative level at which members share many features and are distinct from other categories."},
  {"id":141,"topic":"Concepts","topicIcon":"🗂️","q":"Which level of categorisation is 'furniture' an example of?","opts":["Basic level","Subordinate level","Superordinate level","Exemplar level"],"ans":2,"diff":"easy","expl":"'Furniture' is a superordinate category—it is more abstract and general than the basic level (e.g., 'chair') and the subordinate level (e.g., 'rocking chair')."},
  {"id":142,"topic":"Concepts","topicIcon":"🗂️","q":"The schema-based view of concepts emphasises that:","opts":["Concepts are defined by necessary features","Concepts are embedded in broader knowledge structures (schemas) that provide context","Concepts are represented by prototypes only","Concepts are stored as individual exemplars"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"The schema-based view holds that concepts are understood within the context of larger knowledge structures (schemas), which provide background knowledge and expectations."},
  {"id":143,"topic":"Concepts","topicIcon":"🗂️","q":"The knowledge-based (theory-based) view of concepts proposes that categorisation is driven by:","opts":["Surface similarity to a prototype","Causal and explanatory theories about why things belong together","The number of shared features","Frequency of exposure"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"The knowledge-based view: people use implicit theories and causal knowledge (not just surface similarity) to determine category membership and understand why members belong together."},
  {"id":144,"topic":"Concepts","topicIcon":"🗂️","q":"Bruner's concept attainment study examined how people:","opts":["Recall category labels","Discover the rule defining a concept through hypothesis testing","Form prototypes from exemplars","Use schemas to categorise objects"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Bruner's concept attainment studies investigated the strategies people use to identify the rule (concept) from a series of positive and negative instances."},
  {"id":145,"topic":"Concepts","topicIcon":"🗂️","q":"In Bruner's concept attainment, 'conservative focusing' involves:","opts":["Testing one hypothesis at a time by changing one attribute per trial","Testing all possible hypotheses simultaneously","Randomly selecting instances to test","Focusing only on negative instances"],"ans":0,"diff":"hard","expl":"Conservative focusing: start with a positive instance as a focus card, then change one attribute at a time; if the result is positive, that attribute is irrelevant; if negative, it is relevant."},
  {"id":146,"topic":"Concepts","topicIcon":"🗂️","q":"'Simultaneous scanning' in Bruner's concept attainment means:","opts":["Testing one hypothesis at a time","Considering all possible hypotheses at once and eliminating those inconsistent with each instance","Focusing on a single positive instance","Randomly guessing"],"ans":1,"diff":"hard","expl":"Simultaneous scanning: the learner considers all possible hypotheses simultaneously and eliminates those ruled out by each new instance—cognitively demanding but thorough."},
  {"id":147,"topic":"Concepts","topicIcon":"🗂️","q":"The typicality gradient in prototype theory predicts that:","opts":["All category members are equally typical","Some members are more typical (closer to the prototype) and are processed faster","Atypical members are not category members","Typicality is irrelevant to categorisation"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Prototype theory predicts a typicality gradient: members closer to the prototype are judged as better examples and are categorised faster and more accurately."},
  {"id":148,"topic":"Concepts","topicIcon":"🗂️","q":"Similarity-based categorisation differs from explanation-based categorisation in that:","opts":["Similarity-based uses causal theories; explanation-based uses surface features","Similarity-based groups items by shared features; explanation-based groups items by shared causal/theoretical relationships","They are identical approaches","Explanation-based is always more accurate"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Similarity-based categorisation relies on perceptual or feature overlap; explanation-based (theory-based) categorisation relies on causal and theoretical relationships between features."},
  {"id":149,"topic":"Concepts","topicIcon":"🗂️","q":"Which finding is most problematic for the exemplar view of concepts?","opts":["Typicality effects","The ability to categorise novel items never encountered before","The basic-level advantage","Family resemblance"],"ans":1,"diff":"hard","expl":"The exemplar view struggles to explain how people can categorise entirely novel items they have never seen before, since there are no stored exemplars to compare them to."},
  {"id":150,"topic":"Concepts","topicIcon":"🗂️","q":"'Successive scanning' in Bruner's concept attainment involves:","opts":["Testing all hypotheses simultaneously","Testing one hypothesis at a time, moving to the next if it is disconfirmed","Focusing on a positive instance and changing one attribute","Randomly selecting instances"],"ans":1,"diff":"hard","expl":"Successive scanning: the learner tests one hypothesis at a time; if disconfirmed, they move to the next hypothesis—simple but slow and potentially inefficient."},

  // ── VISUAL MEMORY (15 questions) ─────────────────────────────────────────────
  {"id":151,"topic":"Visual Memory","topicIcon":"🖼️","q":"Paivio's dual coding hypothesis proposes that:","opts":["All information is stored in a single verbal code","Information can be stored in both verbal and imagistic codes, and dual coding enhances memory","Visual information is always remembered better than verbal","Imagery has no effect on memory"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Dual coding theory: concrete words and pictures are encoded in both verbal and imagistic systems, providing two retrieval routes and enhancing memory compared to abstract words encoded only verbally."},
  {"id":152,"topic":"Visual Memory","topicIcon":"🖼️","q":"Bower's (1970) relational-organisational hypothesis showed that memory for word pairs improves when:","opts":["Words are rehearsed repeatedly","Words are encoded as interacting images rather than separate images","Words are presented in alphabetical order","Words are abstract rather than concrete"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Bower found that forming interactive images (e.g., a dog riding a bicycle) for word pairs produced far better recall than forming separate, non-interacting images."},
  {"id":153,"topic":"Visual Memory","topicIcon":"🖼️","q":"The method of loci is a mnemonic technique that involves:","opts":["Associating items with rhyming peg words","Mentally placing items to be remembered at specific locations along a familiar route","Forming interacting images for word pairs","Repeating items aloud"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Method of loci: items are mentally placed at specific locations along a well-known route; at recall, the person mentally 'walks' the route and retrieves each item from its location."},
  {"id":154,"topic":"Visual Memory","topicIcon":"🖼️","q":"The peg word method uses:","opts":["Familiar locations as memory pegs","A pre-memorised set of rhyming words (one=bun, two=shoe) as pegs for new items","Interacting images for word pairs","Spaced repetition"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"The peg word system: a set of rhyming peg words (one-bun, two-shoe, etc.) is memorised; new items are then associated with each peg word via vivid imagery."},
  {"id":155,"topic":"Visual Memory","topicIcon":"🖼️","q":"Shepard and Metzler's (1971) mental rotation experiments showed that:","opts":["Mental rotation is instantaneous","The time to judge whether two 3D objects are the same increases linearly with the angular difference between them","Mental rotation is impossible for 3D objects","Rotation time is unrelated to angle"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Shepard and Metzler found a linear relationship between angular disparity and reaction time, suggesting that people mentally rotate objects at a constant rate, analogous to physical rotation."},
  {"id":156,"topic":"Visual Memory","topicIcon":"🖼️","q":"Cooper and Shepard's experiments on letter rotation demonstrated that:","opts":["Letters are recognised faster when upright","Recognition time increases with angular departure from upright, suggesting mental rotation to canonical orientation","Rotation has no effect on letter recognition","Letters are always recognised in their presented orientation"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Cooper and Shepard showed that recognition time for rotated letters/characters increased with angular departure from upright, consistent with mental rotation to a standard orientation."},
  {"id":157,"topic":"Visual Memory","topicIcon":"🖼️","q":"Kosslyn's scanning experiments showed that:","opts":["Mental images are not spatially organised","The time to scan between two points on a mental image increases with the distance between them","Mental scanning is instantaneous","Mental images are stored as propositions, not pictures"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Kosslyn found that scanning time between locations on a mental image increased with distance, suggesting that mental images preserve spatial relationships (spatial equivalence)."},
  {"id":158,"topic":"Visual Memory","topicIcon":"🖼️","q":"'Spatial equivalence' of mental imagery means that:","opts":["Mental images are identical to photographs","Mental images preserve the spatial relationships of the objects they represent","Mental images are stored as verbal descriptions","Mental images have no spatial properties"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Spatial equivalence: mental images represent spatial relationships in a way that is functionally analogous to the spatial layout of the actual objects or scenes."},
  {"id":159,"topic":"Visual Memory","topicIcon":"🖼️","q":"'Perceptual equivalence' of mental imagery refers to the finding that:","opts":["Imagery and perception use entirely different brain systems","Imagery and perception share many of the same neural and cognitive processes","Mental images are always more vivid than percepts","Imagery is only possible for visual information"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Perceptual equivalence: mental imagery activates many of the same brain regions and cognitive processes as actual perception, suggesting a shared representational system."},
  {"id":160,"topic":"Visual Memory","topicIcon":"🖼️","q":"The interacting images technique improves memory for word pairs by:","opts":["Repeating the words many times","Creating a vivid, interactive mental image linking the two words","Organising words alphabetically","Using spaced practice"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Interacting images: forming a vivid mental image in which the two items interact (e.g., a dog driving a car) creates a stronger associative link than separate images."},
  {"id":161,"topic":"Visual Memory","topicIcon":"🖼️","q":"Tye's principle of 'implicit coding' in visual imagery means that:","opts":["All details of an image are explicitly represented","Some information in an image is only implicitly represented and must be 'discovered' by inspection","Images are stored as verbal codes","Images have no implicit content"],"ans":1,"diff":"hard","expl":"Implicit coding: not all details of a mental image are explicitly represented; some must be derived by mentally inspecting the image, just as one might inspect a real picture."},
  {"id":162,"topic":"Visual Memory","topicIcon":"🖼️","q":"Which mnemonic technique is most effective for remembering an ordered list of items?","opts":["Elaborative rehearsal alone","Method of loci or peg word method","Maintenance rehearsal","Semantic clustering"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"The method of loci and peg word method are particularly effective for ordered lists because they provide a built-in sequence (the route or the numbered pegs) that preserves order."},
  {"id":163,"topic":"Visual Memory","topicIcon":"🖼️","q":"The finding that concrete words are remembered better than abstract words supports:","opts":["Levels of processing theory","Dual coding hypothesis","Interference theory","Decay theory"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Concrete words (e.g., 'apple') can be encoded both verbally and as a mental image (dual coding), giving two retrieval routes; abstract words (e.g., 'justice') are harder to image and rely mainly on verbal coding."},
  {"id":164,"topic":"Visual Memory","topicIcon":"🖼️","q":"Mental rotation studies support the view that mental imagery is:","opts":["Purely propositional (language-like)","Analogue and spatially organised, like a picture","Random and unstructured","Identical to verbal memory"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"The linear relationship between rotation angle and RT in mental rotation studies supports an analogue (picture-like) representation that can be mentally rotated, not a purely propositional one."},
  {"id":165,"topic":"Visual Memory","topicIcon":"🖼️","q":"Pylyshyn's critique of mental imagery research argued that imagery effects could be explained by:","opts":["Dual coding","Tacit knowledge—participants know how physical rotation works and simulate it","Spatial equivalence","Perceptual equivalence"],"ans":1,"diff":"hard","expl":"Pylyshyn argued that mental rotation effects reflect tacit knowledge about how objects rotate physically, not a genuine analogue mental image—participants simulate expected results rather than truly rotating images."},

  // ── LANGUAGE (15 questions) ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
  {"id":166,"topic":"Language","topicIcon":"💬","q":"Which property of natural language means that a finite set of rules can generate an infinite number of sentences?","opts":["Arbitrary","Discrete","Productive","Regular"],"ans":2,"diff":"easy","expl":"Productivity (generativity): the grammar of a language allows speakers to produce and understand an unlimited number of novel sentences from a finite set of words and rules."},
  {"id":167,"topic":"Language","topicIcon":"💬","q":"The arbitrary property of language means that:","opts":["Words follow predictable sound patterns","The relationship between a word's form and its meaning is not inherently motivated","All languages share the same words","Grammar rules are universal"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Arbitrariness: the connection between a linguistic sign (sound/word) and its meaning is conventional, not inherently motivated—'dog' has no dog-like sound."},
  {"id":168,"topic":"Language","topicIcon":"💬","q":"Phonemes are best defined as:","opts":["The smallest units of meaning","The smallest units of sound that distinguish meaning in a language","Rules for combining words into sentences","The study of meaning in language"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Phonemes are the smallest contrastive sound units in a language; changing one phoneme changes the meaning (e.g., /b/at vs /c/at)."},
  {"id":169,"topic":"Language","topicIcon":"💬","q":"Morphemes are:","opts":["The smallest units of sound","The smallest units of meaning","Rules for sentence structure","The study of language use in context"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Morphemes are the smallest meaningful units of language (e.g., 'un-', 'help', '-ful' are three morphemes in 'unhelpful')."},
  {"id":170,"topic":"Language","topicIcon":"💬","q":"Syntax refers to:","opts":["The meaning of words and sentences","The rules governing the structure and order of words in sentences","The study of language use in social context","The sound system of a language"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Syntax is the set of rules that govern how words are combined into grammatical sentences (phrase structure, word order, etc.)."},
  {"id":171,"topic":"Language","topicIcon":"💬","q":"Pragmatics is the study of:","opts":["Sound patterns in language","Word meanings","How context influences the interpretation and use of language","Sentence structure"],"ans":2,"diff":"easy","expl":"Pragmatics examines how context, speaker intentions, and social conventions influence the meaning and use of language beyond the literal meaning of words."},
  {"id":172,"topic":"Language","topicIcon":"💬","q":"Categorical perception of speech means that:","opts":["All speech sounds are perceived as equally distinct","Sounds along a continuum are perceived as belonging to discrete categories with sharp boundaries","Speech perception is continuous and gradient","Listeners cannot distinguish between phonemes"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Categorical perception: listeners perceive speech sounds as belonging to discrete phoneme categories; sounds within a category sound alike, while sounds across a boundary sound very different."},
  {"id":173,"topic":"Language","topicIcon":"💬","q":"Warren's phoneme restoration effect demonstrates that:","opts":["Listeners cannot perceive missing phonemes","Listeners perceptually restore a missing phoneme based on context, without noticing the gap","Missing phonemes always cause comprehension failure","Context has no effect on speech perception"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Warren (1970) replaced a phoneme with a cough; listeners reported hearing the complete word, demonstrating that top-down contextual knowledge restores missing speech sounds."},
  {"id":174,"topic":"Language","topicIcon":"💬","q":"Garden path sentences (e.g., 'The horse raced past the barn fell') demonstrate that:","opts":["Syntax is processed after semantics","The parser initially commits to one syntactic interpretation and must reanalyse when it fails","All sentences are parsed in parallel","Ambiguity is always resolved by context"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Garden path sentences show that the parser initially follows the most common syntactic path; when this fails, costly reanalysis is required, causing comprehension difficulty."},
  {"id":175,"topic":"Language","topicIcon":"💬","q":"Garrett's distinction between form errors and meaning errors in speech production refers to:","opts":["Errors in pronunciation vs. errors in grammar","Errors involving sound/word form (e.g., spoonerisms) vs. errors involving meaning (e.g., semantic substitutions)","Errors in reading vs. errors in speaking","Errors in syntax vs. errors in pragmatics"],"ans":1,"diff":"hard","expl":"Garrett distinguished form-level errors (e.g., spoonerisms: 'blushing crow' for 'crushing blow') from meaning-level errors (e.g., semantic substitutions: 'table' for 'chair'), suggesting separate levels of language production."},
  {"id":176,"topic":"Language","topicIcon":"💬","q":"The word superiority effect refers to the finding that:","opts":["Words are always recognised faster than non-words","Letters are identified more accurately when presented within a word than in isolation or a non-word","Longer words are recognised faster","Familiar words are always recognised"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"The word superiority effect: a letter embedded in a word (e.g., 'K' in 'WORK') is identified more accurately than the same letter in isolation or in a non-word, showing top-down facilitation."},
  {"id":177,"topic":"Language","topicIcon":"💬","q":"Prescriptive grammar refers to:","opts":["Rules that describe how language is actually used","Rules that prescribe how language should be used according to a standard","The study of language evolution","The phonological rules of a language"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Prescriptive grammar specifies how language 'should' be used according to a standard or authority; descriptive grammar describes how language is actually used by speakers."},
  {"id":178,"topic":"Language","topicIcon":"💬","q":"Voicing in consonant production refers to:","opts":["The place in the mouth where the consonant is produced","Whether the vocal cords vibrate during production","The manner in which airflow is modified","The loudness of the consonant"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Voicing: voiced consonants (e.g., /b/, /d/, /g/) involve vibration of the vocal cords; voiceless consonants (e.g., /p/, /t/, /k/) do not."},
  {"id":179,"topic":"Language","topicIcon":"💬","q":"The discrete property of language means that:","opts":["Language is continuous and gradient","Language is composed of distinct, separate units (phonemes, morphemes, words)","Language is arbitrary","Language is productive"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Discreteness: language is built from distinct, categorical units (phonemes, morphemes, words) rather than continuous gradations, allowing precise combinations."},
  {"id":180,"topic":"Language","topicIcon":"💬","q":"Semantics is the study of:","opts":["Sound patterns","Sentence structure","Meaning in language","Language use in context"],"ans":2,"diff":"easy","expl":"Semantics is the branch of linguistics concerned with meaning—the meaning of words, phrases, and sentences."},

  // ── PROBLEM SOLVING (15 questions) ──────────────────────────────────────────
  {"id":181,"topic":"Problem Solving","topicIcon":"🧩","q":"In problem solving, the 'initial state' refers to:","opts":["The goal the solver is trying to reach","The starting conditions of the problem","The operators available to the solver","The constraints on the solution"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"The initial state is the starting point of a problem—the conditions that exist before any solution steps are taken."},
  {"id":182,"topic":"Problem Solving","topicIcon":"🧩","q":"Operators in problem solving are:","opts":["The constraints that limit solutions","The actions or moves that transform one state into another","The goal state","The initial conditions"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Operators are the permissible actions or moves that can be applied to transform the current problem state toward the goal state."},
  {"id":183,"topic":"Problem Solving","topicIcon":"🧩","q":"Well-defined problems differ from ill-defined problems in that well-defined problems have:","opts":["No clear goal","Clearly specified initial state, goal state, and operators","Unlimited possible solutions","No constraints"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Well-defined problems have clearly specified initial states, goal states, and operators (e.g., chess, algebra). Ill-defined problems lack one or more of these specifications (e.g., 'write a good essay')."},
  {"id":184,"topic":"Problem Solving","topicIcon":"🧩","q":"The General Problem Solver (GPS), developed by Newell and Simon, uses which primary heuristic?","opts":["Trial and error","Means-ends analysis","Backward chaining only","Random search"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"GPS uses means-ends analysis: it identifies the difference between the current state and the goal, then selects operators that reduce that difference."},
  {"id":185,"topic":"Problem Solving","topicIcon":"🧩","q":"Means-ends analysis involves:","opts":["Working backwards from the goal to the initial state","Identifying the difference between current and goal states and applying operators to reduce that difference","Randomly applying operators until the goal is reached","Applying all operators simultaneously"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Means-ends analysis: compare the current state to the goal, identify the most important difference, and select the operator that best reduces that difference—repeat until the goal is reached."},
  {"id":186,"topic":"Problem Solving","topicIcon":"🧩","q":"Mental set in problem solving refers to:","opts":["The tendency to use a previously successful approach even when it is no longer optimal","The ability to see a problem from a new perspective","The use of algorithms to solve problems","The goal state of a problem"],"ans":0,"diff":"medium","expl":"Mental set (Einstellung): the tendency to persist with a previously successful problem-solving approach even when a simpler or more appropriate method is available."},
  {"id":187,"topic":"Problem Solving","topicIcon":"🧩","q":"Functional fixedness is the tendency to:","opts":["Use objects only in their conventional ways, preventing creative solutions","Apply algorithms rigidly","Ignore constraints","Use means-ends analysis exclusively"],"ans":0,"diff":"medium","expl":"Functional fixedness: people perceive objects only in terms of their typical function, preventing them from using the object in a novel way needed to solve a problem (e.g., Duncker's candle problem)."},
  {"id":188,"topic":"Problem Solving","topicIcon":"🧩","q":"The Gestalt approach to problem solving emphasises:","opts":["Stimulus-response associations","Insight and restructuring of the problem representation","Algorithmic search","Means-ends analysis"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Gestalt psychologists (Köhler, Wertheimer) emphasised insight—a sudden restructuring of the problem representation that leads to the solution—rather than incremental trial-and-error."},
  {"id":189,"topic":"Problem Solving","topicIcon":"🧩","q":"Wallas's four stages of creativity are:","opts":["Encoding, storage, retrieval, application","Preparation, incubation, illumination, verification","Problem finding, problem solving, evaluation, implementation","Analysis, synthesis, evaluation, creation"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Wallas (1926) proposed four stages: preparation (gathering information), incubation (unconscious processing), illumination (the 'aha' moment), and verification (testing the solution)."},
  {"id":190,"topic":"Problem Solving","topicIcon":"🧩","q":"The nine-dot problem is a classic example of a problem that requires:","opts":["Means-ends analysis","Breaking out of self-imposed constraints (going outside the perceived boundary)","Algorithmic search","Backward chaining"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"The nine-dot problem requires connecting all nine dots with four straight lines without lifting the pen; most people impose an artificial boundary around the dots, which must be violated to solve it."},
  {"id":191,"topic":"Problem Solving","topicIcon":"🧩","q":"Expert problem solvers differ from novices primarily in that experts:","opts":["Use more operators","Have larger working memory capacity","Represent problems in terms of deep structural features rather than surface features","Always use algorithms"],"ans":2,"diff":"medium","expl":"Experts (e.g., chess masters, physics professors) categorise problems by their deep structural features (underlying principles), while novices focus on surface features (superficial appearance)."},
  {"id":192,"topic":"Problem Solving","topicIcon":"🧩","q":"An algorithm in problem solving is:","opts":["A rule of thumb that usually works","A guaranteed step-by-step procedure that will always find the solution","A creative leap to the solution","A heuristic based on experience"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"An algorithm is a systematic, exhaustive procedure that guarantees finding the correct solution if one exists, but may be slow (e.g., trying every possible combination)."},
  {"id":193,"topic":"Problem Solving","topicIcon":"🧩","q":"A heuristic in problem solving is:","opts":["A guaranteed solution procedure","A rule of thumb that is efficient but not guaranteed to find the solution","A type of algorithm","A form of insight"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Heuristics are mental shortcuts or rules of thumb that are efficient and often effective but do not guarantee finding the optimal or correct solution."},
  {"id":194,"topic":"Problem Solving","topicIcon":"🧩","q":"Mayer's 'arrangement problems' require the solver to:","opts":["Transform an initial state through a series of moves","Rearrange given elements to satisfy a criterion (e.g., anagrams)","Induce a rule from examples","Deduce a conclusion from premises"],"ans":1,"diff":"hard","expl":"Arrangement problems (e.g., anagrams, the nine-dot problem) require rearranging given elements into a configuration that satisfies the problem's criterion."},
  {"id":195,"topic":"Problem Solving","topicIcon":"🧩","q":"Verbal protocols (think-aloud protocols) are used in problem solving research to:","opts":["Measure reaction time","Reveal the sequence of mental steps a solver takes","Assess working memory capacity","Measure brain activity"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Verbal protocols require participants to think aloud while solving a problem, providing a window into the sequence of cognitive steps and strategies used."},

  // ── REASONING (15 questions) ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
  {"id":196,"topic":"Reasoning","topicIcon":"⚖️","q":"Deductive reasoning involves:","opts":["Drawing probable conclusions from specific observations","Drawing conclusions that must be true if the premises are true","Generating hypotheses from data","Making decisions under uncertainty"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Deductive reasoning: if the premises are true and the argument is valid, the conclusion must be true. It moves from general premises to specific conclusions."},
  {"id":197,"topic":"Reasoning","topicIcon":"⚖️","q":"Inductive reasoning involves:","opts":["Drawing certain conclusions from premises","Drawing probable conclusions from specific observations or examples","Applying formal logic rules","Solving well-defined problems"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Inductive reasoning: drawing general conclusions from specific observations; conclusions are probable but not certain (e.g., 'all observed swans are white, therefore all swans are white')."},
  {"id":198,"topic":"Reasoning","topicIcon":"⚖️","q":"In syllogistic reasoning, validity refers to:","opts":["Whether the premises are factually true","Whether the conclusion follows logically from the premises, regardless of truth","Whether the conclusion is believable","Whether the argument is persuasive"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Validity is a logical property: an argument is valid if the conclusion necessarily follows from the premises, regardless of whether the premises are actually true."},
  {"id":199,"topic":"Reasoning","topicIcon":"⚖️","q":"Modus ponens is the valid conditional argument form:","opts":["If P then Q; Q; therefore P","If P then Q; P; therefore Q","If P then Q; not Q; therefore not P","If P then Q; not P; therefore not Q"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Modus ponens (affirming the antecedent): If P then Q; P is true; therefore Q is true. This is a valid deductive argument form."},
  {"id":200,"topic":"Reasoning","topicIcon":"⚖️","q":"Modus tollens is the valid conditional argument form:","opts":["If P then Q; P; therefore Q","If P then Q; Q; therefore P","If P then Q; not Q; therefore not P","If P then Q; not P; therefore not Q"],"ans":2,"diff":"medium","expl":"Modus tollens (denying the consequent): If P then Q; Q is false; therefore P is false. This is a valid deductive argument form."},
  {"id":201,"topic":"Reasoning","topicIcon":"⚖️","q":"'Affirming the consequent' is a logical fallacy because:","opts":["It is a valid argument form","The conclusion does not necessarily follow (Q could be true for reasons other than P)","It denies the antecedent","It is always used correctly"],"ans":1,"diff":"hard","expl":"Affirming the consequent (If P then Q; Q; therefore P) is invalid: Q could be true for reasons other than P, so P does not necessarily follow."},
  {"id":202,"topic":"Reasoning","topicIcon":"⚖️","q":"The belief bias effect in syllogistic reasoning refers to:","opts":["Accepting valid arguments regardless of conclusion believability","Accepting conclusions that are believable even when the argument is invalid","Rejecting all emotionally charged conclusions","Applying formal logic rules correctly"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Belief bias: people tend to accept conclusions that match their prior beliefs (believable conclusions) even when the argument is logically invalid, and reject valid arguments with unbelievable conclusions."},
  {"id":203,"topic":"Reasoning","topicIcon":"⚖️","q":"The Wason selection task tests:","opts":["Inductive reasoning ability","Conditional reasoning—whether people correctly test a conditional rule","Analogical reasoning","Syllogistic reasoning"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"The Wason selection task presents a conditional rule (If P then Q) and four cards; participants must select the cards needed to test the rule. Most people fail to select the correct cards (P and not-Q)."},
  {"id":204,"topic":"Reasoning","topicIcon":"⚖️","q":"The availability heuristic leads people to judge the probability of an event based on:","opts":["Statistical base rates","How easily examples come to mind","The representativeness of the event","Anchoring on an initial estimate"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Availability heuristic: people estimate the probability of an event by how easily examples come to mind; vivid or recent events are judged as more probable than they actually are."},
  {"id":205,"topic":"Reasoning","topicIcon":"⚖️","q":"The representativeness heuristic involves judging probability based on:","opts":["How easily examples come to mind","How similar something is to a typical member of a category","An initial anchor value","Statistical base rates"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Representativeness heuristic: people judge the probability that something belongs to a category by how similar it is to the typical member of that category, often ignoring base rates."},
  {"id":206,"topic":"Reasoning","topicIcon":"⚖️","q":"The anchoring heuristic refers to:","opts":["Judging probability by availability of examples","Judging probability by representativeness","Making estimates by starting from an initial value and adjusting insufficiently","Using formal logic rules"],"ans":2,"diff":"easy","expl":"Anchoring: people start with an initial value (anchor) and adjust from it, but typically adjust insufficiently, leading to biased estimates."},
  {"id":207,"topic":"Reasoning","topicIcon":"⚖️","q":"Simon's concept of 'bounded rationality' means that:","opts":["Humans are perfectly rational","Human rationality is limited by cognitive capacity, time, and information, leading to satisficing rather than optimising","Humans are completely irrational","Rationality is culturally determined"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Bounded rationality (Simon): human decision-making is rational within limits—cognitive capacity, time, and available information constrain us to 'satisfice' (find a good enough solution) rather than optimise."},
  {"id":208,"topic":"Reasoning","topicIcon":"⚖️","q":"Kahneman's System 1 thinking is characterised as:","opts":["Slow, deliberate, and effortful","Fast, automatic, and intuitive","Logical and rule-based","Always accurate"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"System 1 (Kahneman): fast, automatic, intuitive, and largely unconscious processing—it operates effortlessly but is prone to biases and heuristics."},
  {"id":209,"topic":"Reasoning","topicIcon":"⚖️","q":"The typicality effect in inductive reasoning means that:","opts":["Typical category members make stronger inductive arguments than atypical members","Atypical members are better inductive bases","All members are equally strong inductive bases","Inductive strength is unrelated to typicality"],"ans":0,"diff":"medium","expl":"Typicality effect in induction: arguments based on typical members (e.g., 'robins have property X, therefore all birds have X') are judged stronger than those based on atypical members (e.g., penguins)."},
  {"id":210,"topic":"Reasoning","topicIcon":"⚖️","q":"The diversity effect in inductive reasoning states that:","opts":["Diverse premises make weaker inductive arguments","Diverse premises (e.g., robins and penguins) make stronger inductive arguments than similar premises (e.g., robins and sparrows)","Diversity has no effect on inductive strength","Only one premise is needed for strong induction"],"ans":1,"diff":"hard","expl":"Diversity effect: an inductive argument is stronger when the premises come from diverse members of a category, because diversity suggests the property is broadly distributed across the category."},

  // ── DECISION MAKING (15 questions) ──────────────────────────────────────────
  {"id":211,"topic":"Decision Making","topicIcon":"🎲","q":"Expected utility theory is a normative model of decision making that prescribes:","opts":["How people actually make decisions","How rational agents should make decisions to maximise expected utility","How emotions influence decisions","How heuristics lead to biases"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Expected utility theory is a normative (prescriptive) model specifying that rational agents should choose the option with the highest expected utility (probability × value)."},
  {"id":212,"topic":"Decision Making","topicIcon":"🎲","q":"A descriptive model of decision making aims to:","opts":["Prescribe how decisions should be made","Describe how people actually make decisions, including biases and heuristics","Maximise expected utility","Eliminate cognitive biases"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Descriptive models (e.g., prospect theory) describe actual human decision-making behaviour, including systematic deviations from rationality."},
  {"id":213,"topic":"Decision Making","topicIcon":"🎲","q":"Tversky and Kahneman's (1981) Asian disease problem demonstrated:","opts":["That people always choose the option with the highest expected value","Framing effects—the same objective outcomes are evaluated differently depending on whether they are framed as gains or losses","That people are perfectly rational","That expected utility theory accurately predicts choices"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"The Asian disease problem showed that when outcomes were framed as lives saved (gain frame), people preferred the certain option; when framed as deaths (loss frame), they preferred the risky option—same outcomes, different choices."},
  {"id":214,"topic":"Decision Making","topicIcon":"🎲","q":"Prospect theory (Kahneman & Tversky, 1979) differs from expected utility theory in that it proposes:","opts":["People maximise expected utility","Outcomes are evaluated relative to a reference point, with losses weighted more heavily than equivalent gains","People are perfectly rational","Probability is always weighted accurately"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Prospect theory: outcomes are evaluated relative to a reference point; the value function is concave for gains and convex for losses, and losses loom larger than equivalent gains (loss aversion)."},
  {"id":215,"topic":"Decision Making","topicIcon":"🎲","q":"Loss aversion in prospect theory means that:","opts":["People prefer certain losses to uncertain losses","The psychological impact of a loss is greater than the impact of an equivalent gain","People always avoid risky options","Gains are valued more than losses"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Loss aversion: losing $100 feels worse than gaining $100 feels good; the pain of losses is approximately twice as powerful as the pleasure of equivalent gains."},
  {"id":216,"topic":"Decision Making","topicIcon":"🎲","q":"Preference reversal in decision making refers to:","opts":["Always choosing the same option","Changing one's preference between two options depending on how the choice is presented or elicited","Preferring losses to gains","Maximising expected utility"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Preference reversal: people's stated preferences between two options can reverse depending on whether they are asked to choose between them or to price them separately—violating rational consistency."},
  {"id":217,"topic":"Decision Making","topicIcon":"🎲","q":"The sunk cost effect (Arkes & Blumer, 1985) refers to the tendency to:","opts":["Ignore past investments when making future decisions","Continue investing in a failing course of action because of past unrecoverable investments","Always choose the option with the highest expected value","Prefer certain outcomes to uncertain ones"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Sunk cost effect: people irrationally continue investing in a project because of past costs that cannot be recovered, even when future prospects are poor."},
  {"id":218,"topic":"Decision Making","topicIcon":"🎲","q":"Psychological accounting (mental accounting) refers to:","opts":["Formal financial accounting","The tendency to categorise and evaluate financial outcomes in separate mental accounts rather than as a whole","Loss aversion","The sunk cost effect"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Mental accounting: people categorise money into separate mental accounts (e.g., 'entertainment budget', 'savings') and treat money differently depending on its source or intended use, violating fungibility."},
  {"id":219,"topic":"Decision Making","topicIcon":"🎲","q":"The framing effect demonstrates that decision making violates which principle of rational choice?","opts":["Maximisation of expected utility","Invariance—rational choices should not depend on how options are described","Transitivity","Completeness"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Invariance: rational choice theory requires that preferences between options should not change based on how they are described (framed). Framing effects violate this principle."},
  {"id":220,"topic":"Decision Making","topicIcon":"🎲","q":"Overconfidence in decision making refers to:","opts":["Underestimating one's abilities","Systematically overestimating the accuracy of one's knowledge or predictions","Always making correct decisions","Avoiding risky options"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Overconfidence bias: people tend to overestimate the accuracy of their knowledge and predictions (e.g., being 90% confident in answers that are correct only 70% of the time)."},
  {"id":221,"topic":"Decision Making","topicIcon":"🎲","q":"The threshold approach to choice suggests that:","opts":["People always choose the option with the highest expected utility","People choose the first option that exceeds a minimum acceptable threshold (satisficing)","People consider all possible options before deciding","People always prefer certain outcomes"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"The threshold (satisficing) approach: rather than optimising, people set a minimum acceptable threshold and choose the first option that meets it—consistent with Simon's bounded rationality."},
  {"id":222,"topic":"Decision Making","topicIcon":"🎲","q":"Cultural differences in decision making suggest that:","opts":["All cultures make decisions identically","Individualistic cultures tend to focus on personal outcomes while collectivist cultures consider group outcomes","Culture has no effect on decision making","Western cultures are always more rational"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Research shows cultural differences in decision making: individualistic cultures (e.g., Western) tend to focus on personal gain, while collectivist cultures (e.g., East Asian) weigh group outcomes and social harmony more heavily."},
  {"id":223,"topic":"Decision Making","topicIcon":"🎲","q":"In prospect theory, the value function is:","opts":["Linear for both gains and losses","Concave for gains (diminishing sensitivity) and convex for losses, with a steeper slope for losses","Convex for gains and concave for losses","Identical to the utility function in expected utility theory"],"ans":1,"diff":"hard","expl":"Prospect theory's value function: concave for gains (each additional gain adds less value) and convex for losses (each additional loss hurts less), with losses weighted more steeply than gains—capturing loss aversion and diminishing sensitivity."},
  {"id":224,"topic":"Decision Making","topicIcon":"🎲","q":"Kahneman's System 2 thinking is characterised as:","opts":["Fast, automatic, and intuitive","Slow, deliberate, effortful, and rule-based","Always biased","Unconscious"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"System 2 (Kahneman): slow, deliberate, effortful, and conscious reasoning—it can override System 1 intuitions but requires significant cognitive resources."},
  {"id":225,"topic":"Decision Making","topicIcon":"🎲","q":"The Arkes and Blumer (1985) sunk cost experiment showed that people who paid more for a ski trip:","opts":["Were more likely to abandon the trip when a better option arose","Were more likely to use the ski trip even when a better option was available, to avoid 'wasting' the investment","Made the same decision regardless of cost","Preferred the cheaper option"],"ans":1,"diff":"hard","expl":"Arkes and Blumer found that participants who paid more for a ski trip were more likely to use it (even when a better free trip was available) to justify the sunk cost—demonstrating the sunk cost effect."},

  // ── PERCEPTION – MODELS (bonus questions) ───────────────────────────────────
  {"id":226,"topic":"Perception","topicIcon":"👁️","q":"Bottom-up (data-driven) processing in perception starts with:","opts":["Prior knowledge and expectations","Raw sensory features that are combined to form a percept","The goal state of the perceiver","Emotional state of the observer"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Bottom-up processing is driven by the stimulus itself: basic features (edges, colours, orientations) are detected and combined to build up a percept without relying on prior knowledge."},
  {"id":227,"topic":"Perception","topicIcon":"👁️","q":"Top-down (theory-driven) processing in perception is driven by:","opts":["Raw sensory data","Expectations, prior knowledge, and context","The physical properties of the stimulus","Retinal edge detectors"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Top-down processing uses prior knowledge, expectations, and context to influence perception—the perceiver's mental state shapes what is perceived."},
  {"id":228,"topic":"Perception","topicIcon":"👁️","q":"Biederman's recognition-by-components theory proposes that objects are recognised from:","opts":["Templates stored in memory","36 basic volumetric shapes called geons","Feature lists without spatial arrangement","Holistic templates"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Biederman proposed that objects are represented as arrangements of ~36 basic geometric shapes (geons), analogous to how phonemes combine to form words."},
  {"id":229,"topic":"Perception","topicIcon":"👁️","q":"Selfridge's pandemonium model uses 'demons' to represent:","opts":["Emotional states","Parallel feature detectors that 'shout' when their preferred feature is present","Serial processing stages","Template matching units"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"In pandemonium, feature demons detect specific features and 'shout' in proportion to how well the input matches their feature; cognitive demons combine feature outputs to identify letters/objects."},
  {"id":230,"topic":"Perception","topicIcon":"👁️","q":"David Marr's three-stage model of visual perception begins with the:","opts":["3D model representation","2.5D sketch","Primal sketch","Object recognition stage"],"ans":2,"diff":"medium","expl":"Marr's first stage is the primal sketch: a 2D representation of intensity changes, edges, and local geometric structures derived from the retinal image."},
  {"id":231,"topic":"Perception","topicIcon":"👁️","q":"In Marr's model, the 2.5D sketch adds information about:","opts":["Object identity","Surface orientation, depth, and relative distances from the viewer","Colour and texture only","Object function"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"The 2.5D sketch incorporates depth, surface orientation, and relative distances—a viewer-centred representation that goes beyond the flat primal sketch but is not yet object-centred."},
  {"id":232,"topic":"Perception","topicIcon":"👁️","q":"Gibson's theory of direct perception argues that:","opts":["Perception requires extensive cognitive processing","The environment provides sufficient information for perception without the need for internal construction","Top-down processing is essential","Templates are required for recognition"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Gibson's direct perception: the rich information in the optic array (texture gradients, optic flow) is sufficient for perception; no internal construction or inference is needed."},
  {"id":233,"topic":"Perception","topicIcon":"👁️","q":"Optic flow, as described by Gibson, refers to:","opts":["The flow of information through the visual cortex","The pattern of apparent motion of objects in the visual field as the observer moves","The spread of activation in the visual system","The flow of light through the lens"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Optic flow is the pattern of apparent motion of objects, surfaces, and edges in a visual scene caused by the relative motion between the observer and the scene—a key source of information for navigation and depth."},
  {"id":234,"topic":"Perception","topicIcon":"👁️","q":"Change blindness demonstrates that:","opts":["The visual system records all details of a scene","People often fail to notice changes in a scene when the change occurs during a visual disruption","Attention is always distributed evenly","Top-down processing is impossible"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Change blindness: people frequently fail to detect changes in a visual scene (e.g., a person changing between cuts in a film) when the change coincides with a visual disruption, showing that perception is selective."},
  {"id":235,"topic":"Perception","topicIcon":"👁️","q":"The context effect in perception refers to:","opts":["The effect of retinal image size on perception","The influence of surrounding objects or prior context on the perception of a target","The effect of attention on feature detection","The role of memory in pattern recognition"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Context effect: the perceived properties of an object are influenced by the surrounding context (e.g., the same circle appears larger when surrounded by small circles than when surrounded by large circles)."},

  // ── ADDITIONAL HISTORY & METHODS (bonus) ────────────────────────────────────
  {"id":236,"topic":"History","topicIcon":"📜","q":"George Berkeley contested Locke's view by arguing that:","opts":["All knowledge comes from heredity","Abstract ideas like truth cannot be conceptualised as mental images","The mind is a blank slate","Consciousness can be broken into parts"],"ans":1,"diff":"hard","expl":"Berkeley argued that abstract ideas (e.g., truth, justice) cannot be represented as mental images, challenging Locke's claim that all mental content consists of associated mental images."},
  {"id":237,"topic":"History","topicIcon":"📜","q":"Descartes' contribution to cognitive psychology includes the concept of:","opts":["Tabula rasa","Mind-body dualism—the mind and body are separate substances","Structuralism","Behaviorism"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Descartes proposed mind-body dualism: the mind (res cogitans) and body (res extensa) are distinct substances, raising questions about how they interact—a foundational issue for cognitive psychology."},
  {"id":238,"topic":"Methods","topicIcon":"🔬","q":"The judgment method in cognitive psychology research uses:","opts":["Reaction time measures","Rating scales on which participants evaluate their cognitive experience","Brain imaging","Protocol analysis"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"The judgment method uses rating scales (e.g., 7-point Likert scales) to capture participants' subjective evaluations of their cognitive processes or experiences."},
  {"id":239,"topic":"Methods","topicIcon":"🔬","q":"A key advantage of using multiple methods in cognitive psychology research is:","opts":["It is cheaper","The limitations of one method can be offset by the strengths of another, providing a more complete picture","It always produces the same results","It eliminates the need for theory"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"Converging operations: using multiple methods with different limitations means that findings consistent across methods are more reliable, and each method's weaknesses are compensated by others' strengths."},
  {"id":240,"topic":"Memory","topicIcon":"🧠","q":"The modal model of memory is also known as the:","opts":["Working memory model","Atkinson-Shiffrin model","Levels of processing model","Connectionist model"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"The Atkinson-Shiffrin (1968) model is called the modal model because it was the dominant (modal) model of memory for many years, proposing sensory register, STM, and LTM."},
  {"id":241,"topic":"Long-Term Memory","topicIcon":"📚","q":"Retroactive interference in LTM occurs when:","opts":["Old memories interfere with new learning","New learning interferes with recall of previously learned information","Decay removes old memories","Encoding failure prevents storage"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Retroactive interference: newly learned material interferes with the recall of previously learned material (new interferes backward with old)."},
  {"id":242,"topic":"Working Memory","topicIcon":"💭","q":"The irrelevant speech effect shows that:","opts":["Meaningful speech in the background improves memory","Irrelevant background speech disrupts serial recall of visually presented items, even when ignored","Background music has no effect on memory","Only attended speech affects memory"],"ans":1,"diff":"hard","expl":"The irrelevant speech effect: unattended background speech disrupts serial recall of visually presented items by interfering with the phonological loop, even though the speech is not consciously attended to."},
  {"id":243,"topic":"Reasoning","topicIcon":"⚖️","q":"The atmospheric effect in syllogistic reasoning refers to:","opts":["The effect of room temperature on reasoning","The tendency to accept conclusions that match the mood (universal/particular, affirmative/negative) of the premises","The effect of context on reasoning","The influence of prior knowledge on conclusions"],"ans":1,"diff":"hard","expl":"Atmospheric effect: the quantifiers and negations in the premises create an 'atmosphere' that biases people toward accepting conclusions with matching quantifiers, regardless of logical validity."},
  {"id":244,"topic":"Decision Making","topicIcon":"🎲","q":"Kahneman and Tversky's prospect theory was awarded the Nobel Prize in Economics in:","opts":["1979","1990","2002","2011"],"ans":2,"diff":"medium","expl":"Daniel Kahneman received the Nobel Prize in Economics in 2002 for his work with Amos Tversky on prospect theory and cognitive biases in decision making (Tversky had died in 1996)."},
  {"id":245,"topic":"Problem Solving","topicIcon":"🧩","q":"Insight problems differ from non-insight problems in that insight problems:","opts":["Can be solved by incremental, step-by-step progress","Require a sudden restructuring of the problem representation for solution","Are always well-defined","Can be solved by algorithms"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Insight problems require a sudden 'aha' moment—a restructuring of how the problem is represented—rather than gradual, incremental progress toward the solution."},
  {"id":246,"topic":"Concepts","topicIcon":"🗂️","q":"The 'family resemblance' structure of natural categories, proposed by Wittgenstein, means that:","opts":["All members share a single defining feature","Members share overlapping sets of features, with no single feature common to all","Categories have strict boundaries","All members are equally typical"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Family resemblance: natural category members share overlapping features (like members of a family), but no single feature is shared by all members—undermining the classical view's requirement for necessary features."},
  {"id":247,"topic":"Visual Memory","topicIcon":"🖼️","q":"Kosslyn's image overflow experiments showed that:","opts":["Mental images have no spatial extent","When imagining an object very close, details 'overflow' the mental image, suggesting images have a limited spatial extent","Mental images are unlimited in size","Imagery is purely propositional"],"ans":1,"diff":"hard","expl":"Kosslyn found that when participants imagined an object very close, they reported that parts of it 'overflowed' the mental image, suggesting that mental images have a limited spatial extent analogous to a visual field."},
  {"id":248,"topic":"Language","topicIcon":"💬","q":"The place of articulation for consonants refers to:","opts":["Whether the vocal cords vibrate","Where in the vocal tract the airflow is constricted (e.g., lips, teeth, palate)","The manner in which airflow is modified","The loudness of the sound"],"ans":1,"diff":"medium","expl":"Place of articulation: the location in the vocal tract where the primary constriction occurs (e.g., bilabial /p/, /b/; alveolar /t/, /d/; velar /k/, /g/)."},
  {"id":249,"topic":"Attention","topicIcon":"🎯","q":"The Stroop effect is a classic demonstration of:","opts":["Selective attention succeeding perfectly","Automatic processing (reading) interfering with controlled processing (colour naming)","Divided attention","Inattentional blindness"],"ans":1,"diff":"easy","expl":"The Stroop effect: naming the ink colour of colour words (e.g., the word RED written in blue ink) is slower and more error-prone because automatic word reading interferes with the controlled colour-naming task."},
  {"id":250,"topic":"Memory","topicIcon":"🧠","q":"Haptic memory is the sensory store for which modality?","opts":["Visual","Auditory","Touch","Olfactory"],"ans":2,"diff":"easy","expl":"Haptic memory is the sensory store for touch information, holding tactile sensations briefly after contact with an object."},
];
